il Kilimo]\n| [[Kenya]]\n| 41\n| Active\n| Nov. 8, 2018\n|-\n| [https://www.kiva.org/about/where-kiva-works/partners/154 Fundaci\u00f3n Mario Santo Domingo (FMSD)]\n| [[Colombia]]\n| 40\n| Active\n| Nov. 8, 2018\n|-\n| [https://www.kiva.org/about/where-kiva-works/partners/559 Banque Populaire du Rwanda (BPR)]\n| [[Rwanda]]\n| N/A\n| Active\n| Nov. 8, 2018\n|-\n| [https://www.kiva.org/about/where-kiva-works/partners/484 Cooperativa de Ahorro y Cr\u00e9dito Norandino]\n| [[Peru]]\n| 31% APR\n| Active\n| Nov. 8, 2018\n|-\n| [https://www.kiva.org/about/where-kiva-works/partners/438 R\u00e9seau de Micro-institutions de Croissance de Revenus (RMCR)]\n| [[Mali]]\n| 26\n| Active\n| Nov. 8, 2018\n|-\n| [https://www.kiva.org/about/where-kiva-works/partners/412 Artisan Alliance at The Aspen Institute]\n| [[United States]], [[Nigeria]], [[Nepal]], [[Mali]], [[Kyrgyzstan]], [[Ghana]], [[Mexico]], [[India]], [[Cambodia]], [[Kenya]], [[Uganda]]\n| 0%\n| Active\n| Nov. 8, 2018\n|-\n| [https://www.kiva.org/about/where-kiva-works/partners/404 Ibdaa Microfinance]\n| [[Lebanon]]\n| 40\n| Active\n| Nov. 8, 2018\n|-\n| [https://www.kiva.org/about/where-kiva-works/partners/386 Kenya ECLOF]\n| [[Kenya]]\n| 40\n| Active\n| Nov. 8, 2018\n|-\n| [https://www.kiva.org/about/where-kiva-works/partners/305 Camfed Zimbabwe]\n| [[Zimbabwe]]\n| 0% APR\n| Active\n| Nov. 8, 2018\n|-\n| [https://www.kiva.org/about/where-kiva-works/partners/288 Babban Gana Farmers Organization]\n| [[Nigeria]]\n| 18% APR\n| Active\n| Nov. 8, 2018\n|-\n| [https://www.kiva.org/about/where-kiva-works/partners/222 UGAFODE Microfinance]\n| [[Uganda]]\n| 51\n| Active\n| Nov. 8, 2018\n|-\n| [https://www.kiva.org/about/where-kiva-works/partners/215 Arvand]\n| [[Tajikistan]]\n| 32\n| Active\n| Nov. 8, 2018\n|-\n| [https://www.kiva.org/about/where-kiva-works/partners/210 Zoona]\n| [[Zambia]], [[Malawi]]\n| N/A\n| Active\n| Nov. 8, 2018\n|-\n| [https://www.kiva.org/about/where-kiva-works/partners/167 PADECOMSM]\n| [[El Salvador]]\n| 33\n| Active\n| Nov. 8, 2018\n|-\n| [https://www.kiva.org/about/where-kiva-works/partners/163 HOFOKAM]\n| [[Uganda]]\n| 47\n| Active\n| Nov. 8, 2018\n|-\n| [https://www.kiva.org/about/where-kiva-works/partners/246 ADICLA]\n| [[Guatemala]]\n| 51\n| Active\n| Nov. 12, 2018\n|-\n| [https://www.kiva.org/about/where-kiva-works/partners/23 Hluvuku-Adsema]\n| [[Mozambique]]\n| 50\n| Active\n| Nov. 12, 2018\n|-\n| [https://www.kiva.org/about/where-kiva-works/partners/367 Thrive Microfinance]\n| [[Zimbabwe]]\n| 69% APR\n| Active\n| Nov. 12, 2018\n|-\n| [https://www.kiva.org/about/where-kiva-works/partners/551 Microhub Financial Services (Pvt) Ltd]\n| [[country]]\n| 74% APR\n| Active\n| Nov. 12, 2018\n|-\n| [https://www.kiva.org/about/where-kiva-works/partners/537 Advans Ghana]\n| [[country]]\n| 78% APR\n| Active\n| Nov. 12, 2018\n|}\n\n===Pre-disbursement of funds===\n\nWhen Kiva began, borrowers had to wait until their loans were funded on the Kiva website to receive the funds. Since then, the system has changed, so that loans are disbursed to borrowers before their stories are posted to Kiva's website.<ref name=\"cgdev\">{{cite web |url=http://blogs.cgdev.org/open_book/2009/10/kiva-is-not-quite-what-it-seems.php |title=Kiva Is Not Quite What It Seems |last=Roodman |first=David |date=2 October 2009 |publisher=Center for Global Development |accessdate=16 January 2010 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130118075941/http://blogs.cgdev.org/open_book/2009/10/kiva-is-not-quite-what-it-seems.php |archive-date=January 18, 2013 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Confusion on Where Money Lent via Kiva Goes |first=Stephanie |last=Strom |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/11/09/business/global/09kiva.html?_r=1&scp=1&sq=Kiva&st=cse |newspaper=New York Times |date=8 November 2009 |accessdate=16 January 2010}}</ref> Disbursing loans sooner has a positive impact on the borrowers, who no longer need to wait weeks to receive their funding and can thus take advantage of time-sensitive business opportunities. This is disclosed on Kiva's site; each loan proposal states whether funds were pre-disbursed. Thus, lenders' loan funds are likely to go to borrowers other than those chosen by the lenders.<ref name=\"cgdev\"/> However, since the pay-back behaviour of the specific borrower chosen by the lender ''does'' influence whether or not the lender gets their funds back (except when an MFI has chosen to cover for borrower defaults), there is at least some connection between the lender and the specific borrower. Whether lenders' preferences are used for lender preference trend analysis by any field partners or Kiva is not stated. Kiva's response has been to keep pre-disbursing but be clearer about the process.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blogs.cgdev.org/open_book/2009/10/matt-flannery-kiva-ceo-and-co-founder-replies.php |title=Matt Flannery, Kiva CEO and Co-Founder, Replies |last=Flannery |first=Matt |date=12 October 2009 |publisher=Center for Global Development |accessdate=16 January 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Full-repayment frequency uncertainty===\n\nWhether defaults are extremely low has been questioned on the ground that a field partner may pay Kiva for loans defaulted to the field partner in order to maintain the field partner's good credit with Kiva.<ref name=\"cgdev\"/> Whether [[interest rate]]s collected by field partners are enough to pay for significant defaults depends on local economic conditions for each field partner.\n\n===Controversial loans===\n\nIn 2008, Kiva featured the borrowing profile of a Peruvian woman asking for a loan to buy equipment for her [[cockfighting]] business.<ref name=\"bloodsports_flannery_blog_post\">{{cite web|url=http://www.socialedge.org/blogs/kiva-chronicles/topics/cockfighting|title=Cockfighting|last=Flannery|first=Matt|authorlink=|date=29 March 2008|work=|publisher=[[Skoll Foundation]]|doi=|url-status=dead|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080506203625/http://www.socialedge.org/blogs/kiva-chronicles/topics/cockfighting|archive-date=2008-05-06|accessdate=15 September 2010|coauthors=}}</ref><ref name=\"bloodsports_sfweekly\">\n{{Cite news\n  | last = Smiley\n  | first = Lauren\n  | coauthors =\n  | title = Kiva's Microloans Underwriting Cockfighting in Peru\n  | newspaper = SF Weekly\n  | location = San Francisco\n  | pages =\n  | language =\n  | publisher =\n  | date =27 February 2008\n  | url = http://www.sfweekly.com/2008-02-27/news/kiva-s-micro-loans-underwriting-cockfighting-in-peru/\n  | accessdate =15 September 2010 }}</ref> This sparked debate among the Kiva Lending Community about the principles of the organization, and many complained that the organization was promoting cruelty to animals. Matt Flannery responded to the debate by providing an overview of the legal issues surrounding the debate, and took a more relativist stance. Flannery wrote on Socialedge.org \u2014 a blog site designed to connect entrepreneurs for social benefit \u2014\n\n<blockquote>I think that allowing our partner to decide which loans to post without much interference is a good thing. We can be paternalistic when we start imposing our moral framework upon societies half a world away. Cockfighting in Peru is legal and part of a rich cultural tradition. It may not be humane or palatable from a Western perspective, but that misses the point. Kiva, the organization, should not be making those decisions. Our lenders should be the ones voting with their dollars.<ref name=\"bloodsports_flannery_blog_post\"/></blockquote>\n\nThis position has caused some lenders to pull their funds (often moving them to other microfinance sites such as [[United Prosperity (organisation)|United Prosperity]], [[Zidisha]].org, [[Wokai]], [[Energy in Common]], etc.). Others who wanted to continue to lend through Kiva created \"Kivans Against Cockfighting Loans\" in May 2009, and, as of June 8, 2012, it has lent $15,625 to borrowers pursuing projects that do not involve the harming of animals.<ref name=\"bloodsports_kacl_team\">\n{{cite web\n  | last =\n  | first =\n  | authorlink =\n  | coauthors =\n  | title = Kivans Against Cockfighting Loans\n  | work =\n  | publisher =\n  | date =\n  | url = http://www.kiva.org/team/kacl\n  | doi =\n  | accessdate =8 June 2012}}</ref>\n\n===Controversy regarding Strathmore University and Opus Dei===\n\nIn Spring 2013, one of Kiva's field partners, [[Strathmore University]], posted many large loans to cover full tuitions for students from low-income regions in Kenya who could not otherwise afford higher education.  Kiva also established a field office on the Strathmore campus.  Shortly after, many lenders raised concerns because Strathmore University is a corporate undertaking of [[Opus Dei]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.strathmore.edu/en/about-strathmore/opus-dei|title=Strathmore University - Opus Dei |publisher=Strathmore University |accessdate=7 October 2013}}</ref> This spawned a debate in the Kiva forums, leading to an open letter from Kiva's CEO Matt Flannery addressing the issue.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://pages.kiva.org/kivablog/2013/08/28/an-open-letter-about-kiva-and-strathmore|title=An Open Letter About Kiva and Strathmore |publisher=Kiva.org |accessdate=7 October 2013}}</ref>\n\n== Promotions and marketing strategies ==\n\nIn March 2012, [[Reid Hoffman]], LinkedIn's co-founder, lent Kiva $1 million. Kiva then allowed 40,000 people to lend $25 for \"free.\" Lenders still choose a borrower, but the borrower will pay back Hoffman instead of the lender who chose them. Kiva hopes that the \"free\" users will lend to more of their projects, and thus increase their overall user base.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://mashable.com/2012/03/15/725000-loans-granted-by-kiva-2-6-billion-to-go/|title=725,000 Loans Granted By Kiva, 2.6 Billion To Go|author=Pan, Joann|publisher=Mashable Business|accessdate=31 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn his 2007 book ''[[Giving: How Each of Us Can Change the World]]'', Bill Clinton covers Kiva.org and the work the organization is currently doing and has done in the past.\n\n== External reviews ==\n\nThe following independent entities have reviewed Kiva.\n\n* On October 1, 2019, charity evaluator [[Charity Navigator]] downgraded Kiva from 4 (out of 4) to 3 stars; Kiva had been top-rated at 4 stars since 2010 (with 1 exception in 2016).<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.charitynavigator.org/index.cfm?bay=search.history&orgid=12978|title=Charity Navigator - Historical Ratings for Kiva|work=Charity Navigator}}</ref>\n* In 2013, foundation [[Google.org]] conducted extensive due diligence on Kiva and awarded it a $3 million Global Impact Award for the creation of Kiva Labs.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.google.com/giving/global-impact-awards/kiva/ |title=Google.org |publisher=Google.org |date= |accessdate=January 5, 2014}}</ref>\n* In 2012, charity evaluator [[Philanthropedia]] awarded Kiva its Top Non-Profit Award based on topic area expert opinions.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.myphilanthropedia.org/top-nonprofits/international/microfinance/2012 |title=International Microfinance 2012 Top Nonprofit Ranking |publisher=Myphilanthropedia.org |date= |accessdate=January 5, 2014}}</ref> \n* In 2011, ''[[The Economist]]'' honored Kiva with its Innovation Award.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.economist.com/node/21540389 |title=Monitor: And the winners were ...|magazine=The Economist |date=December 3, 2011 |accessdate=January 5, 2014}}</ref>\n* In 2010, foundation [[Omidyar Network]] conducted extensive due diligence and awarded Kiva a $5 million grant to scale its impact.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.omidyar.com/about_us/news/2010/08/10/omidyar-network-awards-5-million-grant-kiva-spur-growth-microfinance-unders |title=ON &#124; Omidyar Network Awards $5 Million Grant to Kiva to Spur Growth of Microfinance in Underserved Markets |publisher=Omidyar.com |date=August 12, 2010 |accessdate=January 5, 2014}}</ref>\n* In 2010, Kiva was selected as one of Oprah's Ultimate Favorite Things.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oprah.com/oprahshow/Oprahs-Ultimate-Favorite-Things-2010/31 |title=Kiva Gift Card, Courtesy of Groupon |publisher=Oprah.com |date=November 19, 2010 |accessdate=January 5, 2014}}</ref>\n* In 2009, charity evaluator [[GiveWell]] published a generic critique of giving marketplaces including Kiva and [[Global Giving]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.givewell.org/international-giving-marketplaces|title=Kiva, GlobalGiving and other \"giving marketplaces\" - GiveWell|work=GiveWell}}</ref>, and specific critiques of Kiva.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blog.givewell.org/category/kiva/ |title=Kiva &#124; The GiveWell Blog |publisher=Blog.givewell.org |date= |accessdate=January 5, 2014}}</ref> \n* In 2008, ''[[TIME]]'' magazine named Kiva a Top 50 website.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://content.time.com/time/specials/2007/article/0,28804,1809858_1809952_1811306,00.html |title=Kiva - 50 Best Websites 2008 |work=Time |date=June 17, 2008 |accessdate=January 5, 2014}}</ref>\n* In 2007, [[Skoll Foundation]] conducted extensive due diligence and awarded Kiva a $1 million grant as part of its recognition of the world's best social enterprises.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.skollfoundation.org/tag/kiva/ |title=Kiva \u00ab Skoll Foundation |publisher=Skollfoundation.org |date= |accessdate=January 5, 2014}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n\n* [[Flat rate (finance)]]\n* [[List of microfinance sponsors]]\n* [[Microcredit]]\n* [[Microcredit Summit Campaign]]\n* [[Social entrepreneurship]]\n* [[United Prosperity (organisation)|United Prosperity]]\n* [[Vittana]]\n* [[Wokai]]\n* [[Zidisha]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n== External links ==\n[[File:Wikimedia Kiva community logo.svg|thumb|Logo for the Wikipedian team on Kiva.org]]\n* {{Official website|http://www.kiva.org }}\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20120926100353/http://www.kivafriends.org/ Kiva Friends web forum]\n* {{curlie|/Science/Social_Sciences/Economics/Development_Economics/Microfinance/|Microfinance}}\n* [http://www.phorecast.com/2008/02/01/phorecast-podcast-no-03-%e2%80%93-jessica-jackley-flannery-co-founder-of-kivaorg/ Podcast interview with Jessica Jackley Flannery, Feb 2008]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20071021094359/http://uk.intruders.tv/Premal-Shah-of-Kiva-org-on-microfinance-and-helping-poor-help-themselves_a226.html Interview with Premal Shah, President of Kiva]\n* [https://www.pbs.org/frontlineworld/stories/uganda601/history.html PBS's Frontline - World on Kiva]\n* [http://www.ted.com/talks/jessica_jackley_poverty_money_and_love.html TED: Jessica Jackley: Poverty, money -- and love]\n\n{{Peer-to-peer lending companies}}\n{{Crowdfunding platforms}}\n\n[[Category:Microfinance organizations]]\n[[Category:Non-profit organizations based in San Francisco]]\n[[Category:Peer-to-peer charities]]\n[[Category:Peer-to-peer lending companies]]\n[[Category:American fundraising websites]]\n[[Category:Organizations established in 2005]]\n[[Category:Charities based in California]]\n[[Category:501(c)(3) nonprofit organizations]]\n[[Category:Online nonprofit organizations]]\n\n[[ca:Kiva]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Micro-loan platform}}\n{{other uses|Kiva (disambiguation)}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{update|date=November 2017}}\n{{Advert|date=June 2017}}\n}}\n\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2014}}\n{{Infobox organization\n| name              = Kiva Microfunds<br />(also known as Kiva.org)\n| image             = [[File:Kiva.org logo 2016.svg]]\n| type              = \n| founded_date      = {{Start date|2005|10}}\n| tax_id            = 71-0992446\n| registration_id   =\n| founder           = \n| location          = [[San Francisco, California]], United States\n| coordinates       = <!-- {{Coord|LAT|LON|display=inline,title}} -->\n| origins           = \n| key_people =\n* [[Premal Shah]] (co-founder)\n* [[Jessica Jackley]] (co-founder)\n* Neville Crawley (CEO)\n| area_served       = [[World]]-wide\n| product           = \n| focus             = Economic development\n| method            = [[Microcredit]]\n| revenue           = $19,847,885<ref name=\"ProPublica\">{{cite web|title=Kiva Microfunds|url=https://projects.propublica.org/nonprofits/organizations/710992446|publisher=ProPublica|accessdate=4 September 2017}}</ref>\n| revenue_year        = 2015\n| disbursements       = \n| expenses            = $15,915,830\n| expenses_year       = 2015\n| endowment           = $27,389,839\n| staff               = 117\n| staff_year          = 2015\n| volunteers          = 450\n| volunteers_year     = 2015\n| num_members       = \n| subsid            = \n| owner             = \n| former name       =\n| homepage          = {{URL|kiva.org}}\n| dissolved         = \n| footnotes         = \n}}\n'''Kiva''' (commonly known by its domain name, '''Kiva.org''') is a 501(c)(3) [[non-profit organization]]<ref>{{cite web |url=http://na3.salesforce.com/_ui/selfservice/pkb/PublicKnowledgeSolution/d?orgId=00D500000006svl&lang=1&id=50150000000IIX2&retURL=%2Fsol%2Fpublic%2Fsolutionbrowser.jsp%3Fsearch%3Dnon-profit%26cid%3D02n50000000DUOS%26orgId%3D00D500000006svl%26lang%3D1%26t%3D4&ps=1&pPv=1 |title=What kind of organization is Kiva? |accessdate=10 January 2012}}</ref> that allows people to lend money via the [[Internet]] to low-income entrepreneurs and students in 77 countries.  Kiva's mission is \"to expand financial access to help underserved communities thrive.\"<ref name=\"About\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.kiva.org/about|title=About|website=Kiva|language=en|access-date=2019-07-29}}</ref>\n\nSince 2005, Kiva has [[Crowdfunding | crowd-funded]] more than 1.6 million loans, totaling over $1.33 billion,<ref name=\"About\"/> with a repayment rate of between 96 and 97 percent.<ref name=\"About\"/> Over 1.8 million lenders worldwide use the Kiva platform.\n\nKiva relies on a network of field partners to administer the loans on the ground.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kiva.org/about|publisher=Kiva.org|title=About Us|accessdate=25 April 2013}}</ref> These field partners can be [[microfinance]] institutions, social impact businesses, schools or non-profit organizations.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kiva.org/partners/info|publisher=Kiva.org|title=How to become a Field Partner|accessdate=28 March 2013}}</ref> Kiva includes personal stories of each person who needs a loan so that their lenders can connect with their entrepreneurs on a human level.<ref name=\"Matt Flannery 2007\">{{cite web |url=http://media.kiva.org/INNOV0201_flannery_kiva.pdf |title=Kiva and the Birth of Person to Person Microfinance|publisher=MIT Press|first=Matt |last=Flannery |year=2007|accessdate=4 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nNeither Kiva itself nor its individual lenders collect any interest on the loans it facilitates. However, Kiva borrowers do pay interest on most loans to its Field Partners.<ref name=\"Interest\">{{cite web |url=https://www.kiva.org/about/how |title=How Kiva works |accessdate=6 December 2019}}</ref> Kiva is supported by grants, loans, and donations from its users, corporations, and national institutions.<ref name=\"Supporters\">{{cite web |url=http://www.kiva.org/about/supporters |title=Supporters|publisher=Kiva.org |accessdate=1 April 2012}}</ref> Kiva is headquartered in [[San Francisco]], [[California]].\n\n== History ==\n[[File:Kiva worldwide map.jpg|thumb|250px|Early Kiva field partners (September 2006)]]\nKiva was founded in October 2005 by Matt Flannery and [[Jessica Jackley]].<ref name=\"Matt Flannery 2007\"/> The couple's initial interest in microfinance was inspired by a 2003 lecture given by [[Grameen Bank]]'s [[Muhammad Yunus]] at [[Stanford Business School]]. Jessica Jackley worked at the school and invited Matt Flannery to attend the presentation; this was the first time  Flannery had heard of microfinance, but it served as a \"call to action\" for Jackley. Soon after, Jackley began working as a consultant for the nonprofit [[Village Enterprise]], which worked to help start small businesses in [[East Africa]]. While Flannery was visiting Jackley in Africa, the two spent time interviewing entrepreneurs about the problems they faced in starting ventures and found the lack of access to start-up capital was a common theme. After returning from Africa, the two began developing their plan for a microfinance project that would grow into Kiva, which means \"unity\" in [[Swahili language|Swahili]].<ref>{{Cite journal | last1 = Flannery | first1 = M. | title = Kiva and the Birth of Person-to-Person Microfinance | journal = Innovations: Technology, Governance, Globalization | volume = 2 | pages = 31\u201356 | year = 2007 | doi = 10.1162/itgg.2007.2.1-2.31}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal |last1=Narang |first1=Sonia |year=2006 |title=Web-Based Microfinancing |journal=New York Times Magazine  |url=https://www.nytimes.com/2006/12/10/magazine/10section4.t-6.html?ex=1323406800&en=72e9b0bb93393330&ei=5090&partner=rssuserland&emc=rss |accessdate=10 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn April 2005, Kiva's first seven loans were funded, totaling $3,500, and the original entrepreneurs were subsequently deemed the \"Dream Team.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kiva.org/about/history| title=History| publisher=Kiva.org| accessdate=5 April 2012}}</ref> By September 2005, the entrepreneurs repaid the entirety of their original loans, and the founders realized they had developed a sustainable microcredit concept. After the success of Kiva's initial stage, Flannery and Jackley founded Kiva as a non-profit. In 2006, notable entrepreneurs and businessmen joined Kiva's staff, including [[Premal Shah]] from PayPal and [[Reid Hoffman]], CEO and founder of [[LinkedIn]]. Shortly after its first anniversary in October 2006, Kiva reached $1 million in facilitated loans and acquired its twentieth field partner.{{citation needed|date=December 2013}} To the present day, Kiva has continued to grow and expand its field partners while acquiring support from the media and the public.\n\n== Lending process ==\nKiva works with more than 300 [[microfinance]] institutions, social impact businesses, schools and non-profit organizations around the world, called \"Field Partners,\" that post profiles of qualified local entrepreneurs on the Kiva website. Lenders browse borrower profiles on kiva.org and choose an entrepreneur they wish to fund. The lenders transfer their funds to Kiva through credit card processing or [[PayPal]], which waives its transaction fee in these cases.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://na3.salesforce.com/_ui/selfservice/pkb/PublicKnowledgeSolution/d?orgId=00D500000006svl&lang=1&id=50150000000IDir&retURL=%2Fsol%2Fpublic%2Fsolutionbrowser.jsp%3Fsearch%3Dpaypal%26cid%3D02n50000000DUOS%26orgId%3D00D500000006svl%26lang%3D1%26t%3D4&ps=1&pPv=1 |title=When I pay through PayPal, is PayPal taking a fee? |accessdate=10 January 2012}}</ref> Lenders can loan money in increments of $25.\n\nAfter receiving lenders' money, Kiva aggregates loan capital from the individual lenders and transfers it to the appropriate Field Partners, which  disburse the loan to the borrower. Kiva does not charge interest on the capital sent to Field Partners, but often Field Partners do charge some level of interest to borrowers to cover administration costs.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://na3.salesforce.com/_ui/selfservice/pkb/PublicKnowledgeSolution/d?orgId=00D500000006svl&id=50150000000IIav&retURL=%2Fsol%2Fpublic%2Fsolutionbrowser.jsp%3Fcid%3D02n50000000DV8W%26orgId%3D00D500000006svl&ps=1 |title=Do Kiva.org's Field Partners charge interest to the borrowers? |accessdate=10 January 2012}}</ref> Interest is typically higher on loans from microfinance institutions in developing countries than interest rates on larger loans in developed countries because of the administrative costs of overseeing many tiny loans, and the increased risk.<ref>{{cite web|title=Why are microcredit interest rates higher than traditional interest rates?|url=http://www.microworld.org/en/news-from-the-field/article/why-are-microcredit-interest-rates-higher-traditional-interest-rates|publisher=MicroWorld}}</ref>  As the entrepreneurs repay their loans with interest, the Field Partners remit funds back to Kiva. As the loan is repaid, the Kiva lenders can withdraw their principal or re-lend it to another entrepreneur.\n\n== Finances ==\nAs of March 15, 2016, Kiva had distributed $827,356,850 in loans from 1,394,336 lenders to 1,928,760 borrowers, and a total of 1,036,558 loans had been funded through Kiva.  The average loan size is $411.26, and the average Kiva user has made 10.17 loans. Kiva's current repayment rate for all its partners is 97.1%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kiva.org/about/stats|title=KIVA Stats|publisher=Kiva.org|accessdate=15 March 2016}}</ref> According to [[Alexa Internet|Alexa: The Web Information Company]], Kiva's website ranks in the top 15,000 of all websites worldwide and ranks in the top 5,000 for the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.alexa.com/data/details/traffic_details?site0=kiva.org&site1=&site2=&site3=&site4=&y=r&z=1&h=300&w=610&range=3y&size=Medium&url=kiva.org|title=Kiva.org|publisher=Alexa.com|accessdate=15 May 2013}}</ref>\n\nFor the fiscal year 2012, Kiva made $15,632,786 in total [[revenue]] and had $12,482,528 in total expenses, leaving $3,150,258 to invest. The organization's net assets in 2012 totaled $16,248,638.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cms.kiva.org.s3.amazonaws.com/kiva_microfunds_2012_990.pdf |title=Return of Organization Exempt From Income Tax|publisher=Department of the Treasury Internal Revenue Service|accessdate=April 18, 2014}}</ref> Kiva itself does not charge interest on its loans; they supply capital to microfinancing institutions for free. These microfinancing institutions then lend out money with high interest compared to bank finance in mature markets, averaging a portfolio yield of over 30%.<ref>[http://nextbillion.net/kiva-responds/ Kiva Responds: The famed microlender replies to Hugh Sinclair\u2019s scathing critique], nextbillion.com, 12 February 2014</ref> The organization's main sources of funding are grants, financial backing, and discounted services from many major national corporations and institutions. [[Chevron Corporation]], [[Visa Inc.]], and [[Skoll Foundation]] awarded Kiva a two-year $1 million grant, $1.5 million grant, and $1 million grant respectively. Kiva also won a $1 million grant in [[Sam's Club]]'s \"Giving Made Simple\" campaign and $500,000 in [[American Express]]'s \"Take Part\" competition. Additionally, [[Omidyar Network]] awarded Kiva a $5 million grant over 5 years to help Kiva expand its field partners and support due diligence.<ref name=\"Supporters\"/>\n\n===Management===\nIn 2015, the non-profit employed seventeen persons with salaries totaling more than $100,000. The average salary at Kiva is $80,768.<ref name = ProPublica />\n\n==Areas of work and loan use==\n\n=== Female-owned businesses ===\nAs of October 2017, 81% of Kiva's loans have been made to women.<ref>{{cite web |title=Impact |url=https://www.kiva.org/about/impact |website=Kiva.org |accessdate=13 November 2018}}</ref> Kiva emphasizes supporting women because women can gain the most from [[microcredit]]. [[Patriarchy]] and a strict [[division of labor]] still dominate the societies of many [[developing countries]], and women often suffer the most from [[poverty]] because scarce resources are often allocated to a family's males, rather than its females.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.law.fsu.edu/journals/transnational/vol17_1/RJLee.pdf|title=The Microfinance Movement: Closing the Gender Gap with a Click|author=Jackson Lee, Ruth|accessdate=1 April 2012}}</ref>\n\nIn their non-fiction book ''[[Half the Sky]]'', [[Nicholas D. Kristof]] and [[Sheryl WuDunn]] highlight Kiva's work along with that of some field partner organizations, such as the Kashf Foundation in [[Pakistan]]. With microloans, women gain spending power and spend less on instant gratification vices like alcohol and drugs. With extra income, they are able to educate their children, renovate their residences, or buy modern technologies and medicines. Along with economic power, a woman with a microloan often gains more independence and respect from her husband. Kristof and WuDunn note that microfinance can be a risky path out of poverty. \"[Paying back the loan with interest] is fine when the money is pumped into a profitable new business, but if the money isn't invested soundly, then the borrowers become trapped in mounting debts.\" Nonetheless, the authors endorse Kiva and similar microfinance efforts, writing that \"microfinance has done more to bolster the status of women, and to protect them from abuse, than any laws could accomplish.\"<ref>{{cite book|title=Half the Sky|url=https://archive.org/details/halfsky00nich|url-access=registration|authors=Kristof, Nicholas D., Sheryl WuDunn|publisher=Vintage Books|location=New York|year=2009}}</ref>\n\n=== Green loans ===\nIn 2011, Kiva added a new category of loans to help borrowers move to cleaner and safer forms of energy, green agriculture, transport and recycling.<ref>{{cite web|last=Byrne|first=Ciara|title=Micro-lending site Kiva goes green|url=https://venturebeat.com/2011/04/22/micro-lending-site-kiva-goes-green/|publisher=Venturebeat}}</ref> Green Kiva loans help fund solar panels, organic fertilizers, high-efficiency stoves, [[drip irrigation]] systems, and biofuels. As of December 2013, Kiva lenders had crowd-funded 4,600 green loans.<ref>{{cite web|last=Alois|first=JD|title=Kiva Labs to Generate $25 Million in Crowdfunded Loans for Clean Energy, Mobile Technology, and Agriculture|url=http://www.crowdfundinsider.com/2013/12/28310-google-global-impact-award-gives-kiva-3-million-kiva-labs/}}</ref>\n\n===Support for higher education===\n\nGetting access to university and graduate level education is extremely difficult for poor students in developing countries. Outside of the United States and a few other wealthy industrialized countries, student loans are rare, leaving families without substantial savings, and with few options.<ref>{{cite web|last=White|first=Mercedes|title=Loans for students in developing nations help fight against poverty|url=http://www.deseretnews.com/article/865570151/Loans-for-students-in-developing-nations-help-fight-against-poverty.html?pg=all}}</ref> As of 2007, in low income countries only 7% of the population received university or graduate level education.<ref>{{cite web|title=Global Trends in Higher Education|url=http://www.uis.unesco.org/Library/Documents/trends-global-higher-education-2009-world-conference-en.pdf|publisher=UNESCO}}</ref>\n\nHigher education has been shown to play a significant role in developing a country, and UNESCO reports that \"higher education makes a significant contribution to reduction in absolute as well as relative poverty,\"<ref>{{cite web|last=Tilak|first=Jandhyala|title=Higher education, poverty and development|url=http://www.iiep.unesco.org/fileadmin/user_upload/pdf/jane07.pdf|publisher=UNESCO}}</ref>\n\nIn 2010, Kiva began a Student Microloans program that allowed lenders to help support students seeking access to higher education.<ref>{{cite web|last=Rao|first=Leena|title=Kiva Adds Student Loans To Microlending Marketplace|url=https://techcrunch.com/2010/09/20/kiva-adds-student-loans-to-microlending-marketplace/}}</ref> Student loans are funded with the same crowd-funding approach, and typically students have 1\u20133 years to pay back their loans.\n\nIn 2014, the education offerings on Kiva expanded greatly when the organization began a deeper partnership with [[Vittana]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Farr|first=Christina|title=Kiva and Vittana partner to crowdfund loans for students in developing nations|url=https://venturebeat.com/2014/02/25/kiva-and-vittana-partner-to-crowdfund-loans-for-students-in-developing-nations/}}</ref> Vittana works on the ground in countries in Asia, Africa and Latin America, developing loan alternatives for low-income students. Through the partnership, all loans sourced by Vittana now appear on Kiva for funding.\n\n===Medical loans===\n\nSome Kiva field partners, such as Alivio Capital, specialize in funding medical loans.<ref>{{cite web |title=Alivio Capital, Funded |url=https://www.kiva.org/lend?partner=357&status=funded&sortBy=newest |website=Kiva.org |accessdate=12 November 2018}}</ref> Others may fund medical loans as well as other loans.<ref>{{cite web |title=IMON International, Health+Funded |url=https://www.kiva.org/lend?tag=27&partner=100&status=funded&sortBy=newest |website=Kiva.org |accessdate=12 November 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Al Majmoua, Health+Funded |url=https://www.kiva.org/lend?tag=27&partner=77&status=funded&sortBy=newest |website=Kiva.org |accessdate=12 November 2018}}</ref> A development scholar in [[Ghana]] has suggested that microfinance medical loans can be an effective way to close the gap in medical care access in developing countries.<ref>{{cite journal |title=Microfinance: An Alternative Means of Healthcare Financing for the Poor |journal=Ghana Medical Journal |date=December 2007 |volume=41 |issue=4 |pages=193\u2013194 |url=http://www.ghanamedj.org/articles/December2007/Microfinance%20and%20Health%20Insurance.pdf}}</ref>\n\n===Support for refugees===\n\nIn July 2017, Kiva launched a World Refugee Fund, a $250,000 matching fund to provide support to refugees and host communities in countries including Lebanon, Jordan, and Turkey. As refugees repay the loans, they build a track record in their new locations. The fund is to be followed by a rotating fund of up to $9M in loan capital.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/susanprice/2017/07/06/lending-pioneer-kiva-hits-the-one-billion-mark-and-launches-a-fund-for-refugees/#16fd8cf05dfe|title=Lending Pioneer Kiva Hits The One Billion Mark And Launches A Fund For Refugees}}</ref>\n\n== Other Kiva programs ==\n=== Kiva US ===\n\nIn 2011, Kiva launched Kiva US, a 0% interest peer-to-peer lending pilot program for entrepreneurs in the United States, as part of efforts to \"cut lending costs through technology.\"<ref name=\"Said\">{{cite web|last=Said|first=Carolyn|title=Kiva Zip loans aid low-income U.S. entrepreneurs|url=http://www.sfgate.com/news/article/Kiva-Zip-loans-aid-low-income-U-S-entrepreneurs-4723319.php}}</ref> The loans posted to Kiva US are often from borrowers who have been rejected for loans by traditional banking institutions, but on Kiva US they don't need to be able to produce high credit scores or collateral.<ref name=\"Said\"/> Kiva US uses a system of trustees, who vouch for the borrowers.<ref name=\"Todd\">{{cite web|last=Todd|first=Deborah|title=Pittsburgh pilot program to help finance entrepreneurs morphs into Kiva City |url=http://www.post-gazette.com/business/2014/03/27/Pittsburgh-pilot-program-to-help-finance-entrepreneurs-morphs-into-Kiva-Cities/stories/201403260150}}</ref> Kiva US trustees can be local non-profits, service organizations, businesses, faith organizations or community leaders.<ref name=\"Todd\"/>\n\nThe average loan size for US borrowers is $5,000.<ref>{{cite web|last=Tascarella|first=Patty|title=Kiva City Pittsburgh aims to lend to 100 entrepreneurs within first year|url=http://www.bizjournals.com/pittsburgh/news/2014/03/25/kiva-city-pittsburgh-aims-to-lend-to-100.html?page=all}}</ref> US borrowers average about two years to repay loans.<ref name=\"Said\"/>\n\n=== Kiva Labs ===\n\n[[Google]] awarded a $3 million Global Impact Award to Kiva in 2013 to fund the Kiva Labs project, which looks for ways to increase the flexibility and impact of microfinance.<ref name=\"Dolan\">{{cite web|last=Dolan|first=Kerry|title=Microlender Kiva Gets $3M Grant From Google; Aims To Tackle Microfinance 2.0|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kerryadolan/2013/12/16/microlender-kiva-gets-3m-grant-from-google-aims-to-tackle-microfinance-2-0/}}</ref> Labs initiatives include lowering interest rates, providing more flexible repayment terms that accommodate issues like seasonal profits in farming, and offering longer-term loans for investments like education.<ref name=\"Dolan\"/> Labs also focuses on providing access to clean energy technology and using mobile technology in ways that will bridge the [[knowledge gap]]. At the time of the lab's launch, Kiva lenders had crowdfunded \"132,000 agricultural loans; 4,600 green loans, and 670 mobile tech loans.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Kiva.org Receives $3 Million Google Global Impact Award to Launch Kiva Labs|url=https://finance.yahoo.com/news/kiva-org-receives-3-million-153000050.html}}</ref>\n\n=== Kiva City===\n\nKiva City provides local business owners and entrepreneurs in U.S. cities with the opportunity to [[crowdsource]] loans.<ref>{{cite web|last=Ferenstein|first=Gregory|title=Kiva Piloting Microlending For U.S. Small Biz, Clinton Says It's 'A Very Big Deal'|url=https://techcrunch.com/2013/03/22/kiva-piloting-microlending-for-u-s-small-biz-clinton-says-its-a-very-big-deal/}}</ref> It was launched by Kiva and former US President [[Bill Clinton]] at the [[Clinton Global Initiative]] America conference in Chicago in 2011.<ref>{{cite web|last=Loten|first=Angus|title=Clinton Launches Micro-Lending Drive|url=https://blogs.wsj.com/in-charge/2011/06/29/clinton-launches-micro-lending-drive/}}</ref>  Kiva City locations include:  [[Detroit]], [[New Orleans]], [[Los Angeles]], [[Washington D.C.]], [[Newark, New Jersey|Newark]], [[Richmond va|Richmond]], [[Little Rock]], [[Pittsburgh]], [[Philadelphia]], [[Milwaukee]], [[Louisville]], [[San Francisco]], [[New York City]], and [[Oakland]].\n\nIn less than a year, the Kiva City programs in [[Richmond va|Richmond]], Virginia, helped fund more than $100,000 in loans to local businesses.<ref>{{cite web|last=Geiger|first=Jacob|title=Kiva Zip loan program has lent $100k since launch|url=http://www.timesdispatch.com/workitrichmond/news/kiva-zip-loan-program-has-lent-k-since-launch/article_a0139640-b3a5-11e3-94b3-001a4bcf6878.html}}</ref>\n\n== Issues ==\n\n=== Interest rates ===\n\nAs of November 2018, a total of 1,530,180 loans had been funded on Kiva.<ref>{{cite web |title=Funded Loans |url=https://www.kiva.org/lend?status=funded |website=Kiva.org |accessdate=12 November 2018}}</ref> The following table shows these loans sorted according to interest rate.\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n!Number of loans\n!Interest rate\n|-\n| 150,615\n| 0%\n|-\n| 5,570\n| 0.5-10%\n|- \n| 152,926\n| 10.5-20%\n|-\n| 387,677\n| 20.5-30%\n|-\n| 334,205\n| 30.5-40%\n|-\n| 330,354\n| 40.5-50%\n|-\n| 116,154\n| 50.5-60%\n|-\n| 51,026\n| 60.5% +\n|-\n| 1,653\n| No interest rate listed\n|-\n| 1,530,180\n| '''Total'''\n|}\n\nSome people, including microfinance pioneer [[Muhammad Yunus]], argue that the [[interest rates]] of many microcredit institutions are unreasonably high. In his 2007 book he argues that microfinance institutions that charge more than 15% above their long-term operating costs should face penalties.<ref>{{cite book |title=Creating a World Without Poverty:  Social Business and the Future of Capitalism |url=https://archive.org/details/creatingworldwit00yunu |url-access=registration |last=Yunus |first=Muhammad |authorlink=Muhammad Yunus |year=2007 |publisher=PublicAffairs |location=New York |isbn=978-1-58648-667-9 |page=320}}</ref>\n\nAccording to its web site, Kiva quotes interest rates as the \"self reported average rate charged by the Field Partner to the entrepreneur.\"<ref name=\"HighRates\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kiva.org/about/app.php?page=help&action=InterestRateComparison#AverageInterestRateBorrowerPaysToKivaFieldPartner|title=Kiva Help - Interest Rate Comparison|publisher=Kiva.org|accessdate=10 October 2009|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090803220548/http://www.kiva.org/about/app.php?page=help&action=InterestRateComparison#AverageInterestRateBorrowerPaysToKivaFieldPartner|archivedate=August 3, 2009|df=mdy-all}}</ref> Kiva does not publish the interest rates charged for the individual loans funded through its website.  However, it does publish the average \"Portfolio Yield\" of each of its field partners, as a way for prospective lenders to estimate the cost to the borrower of the loans they consider funding.  The \"Portfolio Yield\" measures the average income earned from the field partner's outstanding loan portfolio.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kiva.org/help/borrowingCostComparison|title=[Kiva Help] Borrowing Cost Comparison|work=kiva.org}}</ref>  Some observers have pointed out that the \"Portfolio Yield\" measure is unreliable, and does not directly reflect the actual price that borrowers are paying for the loans.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://blog.microfinancetransparency.com/whats-wrong-with-kivas-portfolio-yield-statistic/ | date=22 October 2012 | title = What's Wrong With Kiva's Portfolio Yield Statistic? | first = Hugh | last = Sinclair | accessdate=16 January 2013}}</ref>\n\nKiva defends the interest rates of its field partners, however, saying its field partners provide much better rates than local alternatives, but must charge what they do because \"the costs of making a micro-loan in the developing world are higher versus larger loans in the West.\"<ref name=\"HighRates\"/> Kiva itself does not keep any of the interest collected, but operates instead exclusively on donations.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.kiva.org/about |title=Kiva - About Us|accessdate=18 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nFor example, in 2009, micro-loans from Kiva partners in [[Guatemala]] averaged 23.16% for the equivalent of US$430 lent on average, comparable to the commercial [[BanRural]] rate of 24.5% for a loan of US$635.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://lacuadraonline.com/featured-stories/the-coffee-trade-nothing-fair-about-it/3/ |title=The Coffee Trade Nothing Fair About It |last=Shearer |first=Laura |date=15 April 2009 |publisher=La Cuadra |accessdate=10 January 2012}}</ref> (For reference, the [[inflation rate]] for Guatemala typically varies between 5 and 10% and was just 0.62% in 2009).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/idUSN0734249820090707 |title=Guatemala inflation rate drops to 25-year low |publisher=Reuters |date=7 July 2009 |accessdate=10 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nThe high interest rates inherent in the Kiva model have inspired several other online microlending services which aim to reduce the cost to borrowers.  One example, [[United Prosperity (organisation)|United Prosperity]], uses lender funds as security to leverage matching loan amounts from local banks, at lower interest rates than would otherwise be available to the borrowers.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unitedprosperity.org/us/how_up_works |title=United Prosperity - How It Works |accessdate=16 January 2014}}</ref>  United Prosperity works with field partners in India and Sri Lanka.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.unitedprosperity.org/us/our_partners |title=United Prosperity - Our Partners |accessdate=26 May 2015}}</ref>\n\nKiva itself launched a more direct peer-to-peer microlending platform, called Kiva Zip, in 2012.  Kiva Zip transfers funds directly to borrowers without outsourcing disbursements and repayment collection to field partners.  Instead, Kiva Zip partners with local institutions called Trustees, who vet loan applicants, provide mentorship, and may post profiles and updates on their behalf.  Currently, Kiva Zip borrowers do not pay any interest or fees.  Lenders are protected from currency risk but do not earn interest.  Kiva Zip is considered an experimental platform, and offers loans in the United States and in Kenya.  In the future, it hopes to expand to other locations.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://zip.kiva.org/faq# |title=Kiva Zip: FAQ|accessdate=26 May 2015}}</ref>  Kiva Zip's repayment rate is 89.4%.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://zip.kiva.org/|title=Kiva Zip: Innovations in Person-to-Person Lending|accessdate=26 May 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150428142613/https://zip.kiva.org/|archive-date=April 28, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n====Interest rates by field partner====\n\nAs of November 2018, there are a total of 332 field partners listed on the Kiva website and their status is as follows: 173 Active, 41 Inactive, 14 Paused, and 104 Experimental. In addition, 178 former field partners are listed as Closed.<ref name=\"kiva.org\">{{cite web |title=Where Kiva works |url=https://www.kiva.org/about/where-kiva-works |website=Kiva.org |accessdate=10 November 2018}}</ref>\n\nThe following table shows the \"portfolio yield\" of a sampling of field partners. \"Portfolio yield\" figures are calculated by dividing all interest and fees paid by borrowers to the field partner by the average loan portfolio of the field partner that given year. The figure provides a more accurate insight into the costs of borrowing because it includes fees associated with borrowing.\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable collapsible collapsed\"\n|-\n!Field partner<ref name=\"kiva.org\"/>\n!Region\n!Portfolio yield %\n!Status\n!Correct on\n|-\n| [https://www.kiva.org/about/where-kiva-works/partners/48 IMPRO]\n| [[Bolivia]]\n| 20\n| Active\n| Nov. 10, 2018\n|-\n| [https://www.kiva.org/about/where-kiva-works/partners/59 Fundaci\u00f3n Pro Mujer]\n| [[Bolivia]]\n| 32\n| Active\n| Nov. 10, 2018\n|-\n| [https://www.kiva.org/about/where-kiva-works/partners/9 KREDIT, a partner of World Relief]\n| [[Cambodia]]\n| 23\n| Active\n| Nov. 10, 2018\n|-\n| [https://www.kiva.org/about/where-kiva-works/partners/106 Hattha Kaksekar Limited (HKL), a partner of Save the Children]\n| [[Cambodia]], [[Thailand]]\n| 20\n| Active\n| Nov. 10, 2018\n|-\n| [https://www.kiva.org/about/where-kiva-works/partners/61 MAXIMA Microfinance]\n| [[Cambodia]]\n| 22\n| Active\n| Nov. 10, 2018\n|-\n| [https://www.kiva.org/about/where-kiva-works/partners/40 Grounded and Holistic Approach for People's Empowerment (GHAPE)]\n| [[Cameroon]]\n| 20\n| Active\n| Nov. 10, 2018\n|-\n| [https://www.kiva.org/about/where-kiva-works/partners/44 Esp