{"title_page": "Graham Linehan", "text_new": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Irish screenwriter}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox comedian\n| image = Graham Linehan - 2013 (8735745502) (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Linehan in 2013\n| name = Graham Linehan\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1968|5|22|df=yes}}<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=Glinner |number=205073702465970176 |date=22 May 2012 |title=Anyway, bed. Thanks for the conversation. And the birthday wishes! Yay! 44! Not long now! |access-date=15 February 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Dublin]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\n| medium = [[Television]], [[film]], [[twitter]]\n| nationality = Irish\n| spouse = Helen Serafinowicz\n| children = 2\n| active = 1991\u2013present \n| genre = [[Observational comedy]], [[surreal humour]]\n| notable_work = ''[[Father Ted]]'', ''[[The IT Crowd]]''\n}}\n\n'''Graham Linehan''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|l|\u026a|n|\u0259|h|\u00e6|n}}, born 22 May 1968) is an Irish comedian who, in collaboration with [[Arthur Mathews (writer)|Arthur Mathews]], has written or co-written a string of television comedies. He created or co-created the sitcoms ''[[Father Ted]]'', ''[[Black Books]]'' and ''[[The IT Crowd]]''.\n\nHe has also written for ''[[Count Arthur Strong (TV series)|Count Arthur Strong]]'', ''[[Brass Eye]]'' and ''[[The Fast Show]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\n\nLinehan attended Plunkett's School in [[Whitehall, Dublin|Whitehall]], followed by [[Catholic University School]], a [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] secondary school for boys located on the southside of central [[Dublin]], before joining ''[[Hot Press]]''.<ref name =\"Church\">{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/graham-linehan-ive-come-to-hate-the-church-8665386.html |title=Graham Linehan: 'I've come to hate the church' |first=Gerard |last=Gilbert |work= [[The Independent]] |date=22 June 2013 |accessdate=21 October 2014}}</ref> He also had a column with the magazine In Dublin before moving to [[London]].\n\nLinehan is married to writer Helen Serafinowicz who is the sister of [[Peter Serafinowicz]]; the couple have two children.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jones|first1=Alice|title=Inside the comic world of Peter Serafinowicz: The spoof video master is heading to Hollywood|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/inside-the-comic-world-of-peter-serafinowicz-the-spoof-video-master-is-heading-to-hollywood-10279558.html|accessdate=12 July 2015|work=The Independent|date=30 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=guardian>{{cite news|last1=Edemariam|first1=Aida|title=The Saturday Interview: Graham Linehan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2011/jun/11/the-saturday-interview-graham-linehan|accessdate=12 July 2015|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=11 June 2011}}</ref><ref name=Telegraph15>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/11342851/Graham-Linehan-interview-On-the-streets-Twitter-trolls-would-be-considered-sociopaths.html|title=Graham Linehan interview: 'On the streets, Twitter trolls would be considered sociopaths'|first=Guy|last=Kelly|work=The Telegraph|date=16 January 2015}}</ref> In October 2015, Graham and Helen Linehan worked with [[Amnesty International]] on a campaign film calling on the Irish government to repeal [[Eighth Amendment of the Constitution of Ireland|the Eighth Amendment of the Constitution]], which \"acknowledges the right to life of the unborn and, with due regard to the equal right to life of the mother, guarantees in its laws to respect, and, as far as practicable, by its laws to defend and vindicate that right\". The couple revealed their decision for Helen to [[Abortion|abort]] a foetus with [[acrania]] while living in [[England]] in 2004, and their discovery that undergoing the procedure in [[Ireland]] would have been an offence carrying a maximum 14-year prison sentence.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/oct/19/graham-helen-linehan-ireland-abortion-amnesty-international |title=How heartbreak led Helen and Graham Linehan to campaign for abortion in Ireland |last=Gentleman |first=Amelia |date=19 October 2015 |work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nLinehan is an [[Atheism|atheist]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://whythatsdelightful.wordpress.com/2008/09/18/a-bad-day-for-atheism/|title=A bad day for atheism|date=18 September 2008}}</ref> and in January 2009 helped to publicise the [[Atheist Bus Campaign]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/jan/06/atheist-bus-campaign-nationwide|title=Launch of the Atheist Bus Campaign|work=The Guardian|date=6 January 2009}}</ref> He is also an honorary associate of the [[National Secular Society]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.secularism.org.uk/honoraryassociates.html|title=Honorary Associates|website=www.secularism.org.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-01}}</ref>\n\nLinehan announced in June 2018 that he was a survivor of [[testicular cancer]].<ref name=\"linehan251\">{{cite podcast |title=Graham Linehan on his cancer journey and Father Ted - The Musical: Episode 251 |url=https://soundcloud.com/an-irishman-abroad/graham-linehan-on-his-cancer-journey-and-father-ted-the-musical-episode-251 |author=Jarlath Regan |edition=251 |date=3 July 2018 |work=[[An Irishman Abroad]] |via=[[SoundCloud]] |accessdate=4 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nLinehan is an active [[Twitter]] user.<ref name=Telegraph15 /> In 2011 he perpetrated a Twitter hoax around [[Osama Bin Laden]] being a fan of ''[[The IT Crowd]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-13467407|title=Bin Laden and The IT Crowd: Anatomy of a Twitter hoax|date=23 May 2011|work=The Guardian}}</ref> On Friday 13 February 2009, Linehan hosted the first BadMovieClub<ref>{{cite web|url=http://badmovieclub.co.uk |title=BadMovieClub website |publisher=Badmovieclub.co.uk |date= |accessdate=20 August 2009}}</ref> on Twitter.  At 9pm exactly, over 2,000 Twitter users simultaneously pressed 'Play' on the film ''[[The Happening (2008 film)|The Happening]]'' (dir. [[M. Night Shyamalan]] 2008) and continued to tweet whilst watching, creating a collective viewing experience which generated 40,000 tweets in under 2 hours. The BadMovieClub was repeated at 12 midnight on Saturday 14 February, hosted by [[Phill Jupitus]]. In August 2009, when the [[National Health Service]] was being attacked by the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] of the [[United States]] during an attempt by [[President of the United States|President]] [[Barack Obama]] to reform the American healthcare system, Linehan created the #welovetheNHS campaign on Twitter in an attempt to fight back in defence of the NHS.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/news/articles/politics/international_politics/linehan+attacks+american+aposliesapos+over+nhs/3308762.html|title=Linehan attacks American 'lies' over NHS|publisher=[[Channel 4]] |date=14 August 2009|accessdate=17 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| last=Jacobson|first=Seth|url=http://www.theweek.co.uk/technology/20567/how-father-ted-creator-graham-linehan-sparked-nhs-backlash-twitter|title=How Father Ted creator Graham Linehan sparked NHS backlash on Twitter|work=[[The First Post]]|date=12 August 2009|accessdate=17 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\nLinehan and Mathews first met while working at ''[[Hot Press]]''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Thompson |first=Ben |title=Sunshine on Putty: The Golden Age of British Comedy from Vic Reeves to The Office |year=2010 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VH_MuFWd0vMC&dq=isbn:9780007375530 |page=289 |publisher=Harper Collins |isbn=9780007375530 |type=eBook |accessdate=22 June 2012}}</ref> In their early collaborations, they were responsible for segments in many sketch shows, including ''[[Alas Smith and Jones]]'', ''[[Harry Enfield and Chums]]'', ''[[The All New Alexei Sayle Show]]'', ''[[The Day Today]]'' and the [[Ted and Ralph]] characters in ''[[The Fast Show]]'' (the characters were created by Linehan and Mathews and played by [[Paul Whitehouse]] and [[Charlie Higson]]). The two men continued their collaboration with ''[[Paris (1994 TV series)|Paris]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/guide/tv/paris/|title=Paris|publisher=[[British Comedy Guide]]}}</ref> (one series, 1994) and ''[[Father Ted]]'' (three series, 1995\u20131998).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/newsfeatures/1996/0425/96042500102.html|title=Daftness should be mandatory in Irish politics|author=Mary Cummins|date=4 April 1996|work=[[Irish Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/weekend/1998/0502/98050200230.html|title=Life after Ted|author=Deirdre Falvey|date=5 May 1998|work=[[Irish Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2007/0121/ted.html|title=Aran Islands in Father Ted row|date=21 January 2007|publisher=[[RT\u00c9]]}}</ref>  They then wrote the first series of the [[sketch comedy|sketch show]] ''[[Big Train]]'', but Linehan was not involved in the second series.<ref name=digitalfix>{{Cite web | title = Big Train at 20 - interview with Arthur Matthews | work = The Digital Fix | date = 23 July 2018 | accessdate = 13 August 2018 | url = https://www.thedigitalfix.com/television/content/11789/big-train-at-20-an-interview-with-the-shows-co-creator-arthur-matthews/}}</ref>\n\nThey also wrote the \"Dearth of A Salesman\" episode for the series ''[[Coogan's Run]]'', which featured the character Gareth Cheeseman. In late 2003, they were named one of the 50 funniest acts to work in television by ''[[The Observer]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2003/dec/07/comedy.thebestofbritishcomedy|title=The A-Z of laughter (part two)|date=7 December 2003|work=[[The Observer]]}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Graham Linehan and Jon Ronson at TAM London 2010.jpg|thumb|Graham Linehan with [[Jon Ronson]] at TAM London 2010]]\nLinehan has since written for other shows, including ''[[Brass Eye]]''. With [[Dylan Moran]], he co-wrote the first series of ''[[Black Books]]'', a series to which Mathews also contributed. Linehan has also contributed material to ''[[Blue Jam]]'', and its television adaptation ''[[Jam (TV series)|Jam]]''.\n\nLinehan wrote and directed the 2006 [[Channel 4]] [[situation comedy|sitcom]] ''[[The IT Crowd]]'', in which he sought to move away from the recent British trend towards [[mockumentary|mock-documentary]] comedies. Unlike many series of the time, it was recorded before a studio audience.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/guide/tv/the_it_crowd/interview/|title=The IT Crowd Interviews|year=2006|publisher=[[British Comedy Guide]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/weekend/2006/0121/1137626794008.html|title=Brian Boyd: Have You Tried Turning It Off and On Again?|date=21 January 2006|work=[[Irish Times]]}}</ref> In November 2008, he was awarded an [[Emmy Award#International Emmys|International Emmy]] for ''[[The IT Crowd]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2008/1126/1227486583337.html|title=Linehan wins an Emmy for sitcom on the IT set|author=Shane Hegarty|date=26 November 2008|work=[[Irish Times]]}}</ref> In 2013, he wrote and directed ''[[The Walshes]]''. He co-wrote the first series of the BBC sitcom ''[[Motherland (TV series)|Motherland]]'' and directed its pilot episode.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dowell |first1=Ben |title=BBC orders a full series of middle-class mum sitcom Motherland |url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/2016-10-06/bbc-orders-a-full-series-of-middle-class-mum-sitcom-motherland/ |website=Radio Times |accessdate=15 October 2019 |language=en}}</ref> In 2018 he and Matthews announced plans for a ''Father Ted'' musical.<ref name=digitalfix/>\n\n===Books===\n\nLinehan and Mathews have had one book published, ''Father Ted: The Complete Scripts'' (Paperback \u2013 Boxtree \u2013 20 October 2000) {{ISBN|0-7522-7235-7}}. They have contributed to various magazines and written surreal liner notes for the popular ''[[Volume magazine|Volume]]'' series of [[alternative music]] compilations.\n\n===Television appearances===\n\nBoth Linehan and Mathews have made cameo appearances in programmes they have written. They also made an appearance in the [[sitcom]] ''[[I'm Alan Partridge]]'' as two Irish TV producers considering [[Alan Partridge]] ([[Steve Coogan]]) for a contract.\n\nLinehan has also appeared in ''[[The Day Today]]'' and in two episodes of ''[[Garth Marenghi's Darkplace]]'', and has had cameos in ''[[Black Books]]'' (series one, episode two, as \"I love books\" Guy, and series one, episode five as Fast Food Customer), and the ''[[Father Ted]]'' episodes \"Good Luck Father Ted\", \"Entertaining Father Stone\", \"Flight Into Terror\", \"Cigarettes, Alcohol and Rollerblading\" and \"Chirpy Burpy Cheap Sheep\". He had cameos in four episodes of ''The IT Crowd'': as Messy Joe's Restaurant Musician, in series one, episode three; the blind sorcerer, in series two, Episode six; as an audience member of Jen's speech, in series three, episode four; and as Beth Gaga Shaggy, in series four, episode three. He appeared in the [[List of rounds in Never Mind the Buzzcocks#Identity Parade|Identity Parade]] round of ''[[Never Mind the Buzzcocks]]''. He has also appeared in the pilot of ''[[Little Britain]]'', as well as in series one, episode four, as a bystander who gets in the way of character [[Kenny Craig]] when he is attempting to hypnotise, from a distance, a man whose car he has crashed into. He also appeared in series one, episode five, in which he played a journalist called Roy Sloan (from ''[[Whizzer and Chips]]'') during a conference with Prime Minister Michael Stevens ([[Anthony Head]]). Linehan was one of the writers interviewed by [[Charlie Brooker]] in a special interview episode of the fifth series of ''Brooker's [[Screenwipe]]'' programme, and again on ''Brooker's [[Gameswipe]]'' in 2010. Linehan also appeared as a guest panellist on ''[[Have I Got News for You]]'' in 2011 and again in 2012, and he made his debut as a guest on the BBC show ''[[QI]]'' in the 11th series (K series) in 2013, receiving a score of \u221219.\n\nIn 2007, a documentary about Linehan, his life and his career was produced by Wildfire Films for [[RT\u00c9 One]]. This documentary explored the art, craft and deeply competitive business of creating contemporary television comedy. The programme features interviews with several of the UK's most successful television comedy writers and performers including [[Steve Coogan]], [[Matt Lucas (comedian)|Matt Lucas]], [[David Walliams]], [[Paul Whitehouse]], [[Griff Rhys Jones]] and [[Ardal O'Hanlon]], all of whom have worked with Linehan. It was directed by Adrian McCarthy and produced by Martha O'Neill and Adam Rynne. In 2011, Linehan also appeared with several members of the cast in [[Channel 4]]'s ''Father Ted Night'', an evening of the writer's favourite episodes and two retrospective documentaries.\n\n===Radio appearances===\n\nOn 6 June 2011, Linehan appeared on BBC Radio 4's ''[[Today (BBC Radio 4)|Today]]'' programme to discuss [[The Ladykillers (play)|his adaptation]] of the Ealing comedy film ''[[The Ladykillers]]'' for the West End stage. During this appearance, Linehan took issue with ''[[Today (BBC Radio 4)|Today]]'' presenter [[Justin Webb]] over what he saw as the attempted staging of an artificial argument between himself and the critic [[Michael Billington (critic)|Michael Billington]]. He later expanded on this criticism in an article published in ''[[The Guardian]]'', saying \"I'm talking about that very specific, very artificial, very ''Today'' programme format of a presenter acting as referee between two people who have been chosen to represent the opposing sides of a manufactured argument. It is a binary view of politics, of life and, as a result, it is also a dishonest one. Replace it with anything \u2013 anything \u2013 because anything would be better\".<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/jun/08/today-programme-the-ladykillers-graham-linehan | work=The Guardian | first=Graham | last=Linehan | title=Graham Linehan: My Today programme ambush | date=8 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Other work===\nLinehan's children voiced characters in the 2012 ''[[Adventure Time]]'' episode \"[[Goliad (Adventure Time)|Goliad]]\", with Linehan directing the children while taking the producers' instructions over the phone. Linehan planned to write a sequel episode, and sent versions of the story to the production team.<ref>Ward, Pendleton (Series creator). 2014. \"Goliad\" [Commentary track], ''Adventure Time'' Season Four [DVD], Los Angeles, CA: [[Cartoon Network]].</ref> This episode was never made as ''Adventure Time'' ended in 2018.\n\n== Anti-transgender activism ==\n\nLinehan has tweeted extensively about [[transgender]] issues, which he became involved in after the airing of a 2008 episode of ''[[The IT Crowd]]'', written by Linehan, drew criticism on Twitter for its storyline in which a character unknowingly dates a trans woman.<ref name=\"irishtimes\"/> Linehan felt the joke had been \"harmless\" and says he did not understand the \"ferocity\" of the response.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Haugh |first1=Ben |title=Father Ted creator Linehan creates own social network to defy Twitter after transgender row |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/father-ted-creator-linehan-creates-own-social-network-to-defy-twitter-after-transgender-row-cfzw7xls0 |accessdate=11 February 2020 |work=The Times |date=18 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nLinehan has described himself as being sceptical of the [[self-identification]] of gender, objecting to \"privileged white people saying you must accept anyone who says they are a woman\". He has said that \"anyone suffering from [[gender dysphoria]] needs to be helped and supported\", and has voiced concern over early transgender intervention for children.<ref name=\"irishtimes\">{{cite news |last1=Falvey |first1=Deirdre |title=Graham Linehan: Trans activists 'don't realise the damage' they do |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/tv-radio-web/graham-linehan-trans-activists-don-t-realise-the-damage-they-do-1.3765979 |accessdate=30 May 2019 |work=The Irish Times |date=21 January 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, Stephanie Hayden, a transgender woman, sued Linehan for harassment. Hayden alleged that Linehan had shared photos on Twitter of Hayden's family and her life before transition, suggested she was a criminal by revealing a past conviction, and repeatedly [[misgender]]ed her and [[deadname]]d her by using her previous name.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lyons |first1=Izzy |title=Transgender lawyer launches UK's first 'deadnaming' case against Father Ted writer Graham Linehan |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/10/07/transgender-lawyer-launches-uks-first-deadnaming-case-against/ |accessdate=2 June 2019 |work=The Telegraph |date=7 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/father-ted-writer-graham-linehan-warned-by-police-after-trolling-transgender-activist-wqfwqgsxn|title=Father Ted writer Graham Linehan warned by police after 'trolling' transgender activist|last=Coyle|first=Colin|date=2018-10-07|work=The Sunday Times|access-date=2018-10-07|language=en|issn=0956-1382}}</ref> Linehan in turn alleged that Hayden publicised several private addresses linked to his family to silence him.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2018/oct/07/graham-linehan-police-warning-complaint-by-stephanie-hayden-transgender-activist-twitter|title=Graham Linehan given police warning after complaint by transgender activist|last=Halliday|first=Josh|date=2018-10-07|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-02-20|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Linehan was issued with a verbal warning by police not to contact Hayden.<ref>{{cite news |title=Father Ted writer given harassment warning |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-45777689 |accessdate=2 June 2019 |date=7 October 2018}}</ref>  \n\nLinehan has compared the medical transition of children to experiments carried out on children in [[Nazi Germany]], saying \"if you were around the time of something terrible happening like Nazism, would you be one of the people who said, 'This is wrong,' despite being opposed?\" In the same interview, he described the trans movement as \"provid[ing] cover\" for \"fetishists, con-men, and simply abusive misogynists\".<ref>{{cite av media | people=Derrick Jensen and Graham Linehan | date=9 December 2018 | title=Resistance Radio - Guest: Graham Linehan | type=Podcast | language=English | url=https://resistanceradioprn.podbean.com/e/resistance-radio-guest-graham-linehan/ | publisher=Podbean | quote=The opposition is so extreme and so frightening that eventually everyone is asking you to stop. \u2018My feeling is that I can\u2019t, because it\u2019s too important. It\u2019s too important to the women in my life and it\u2019s too important to me. \u2018I\u2019m now in a position where I can now answer the question honestly of, if you were around the time of something terrible happening like Nazism, or whatever it happened to be, would you be one of the people who said, \u201cNo, this is wrong\u201d, despite being opposed? I feel happy in myself that I\u2019ve been one of the people standing up and saying \u201cno, this is wrong\u201d, despite everybody telling me not to do it.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url=https://inews.co.uk/news/graham-linehan-father-ted-writer-trans-activism-nazism-187701 | title=Father Ted writer Graham Linehan compares the trans movement to Nazism | work=iNews | access-date=2019-10-06 | language=en-UK}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.attitude.co.uk/article/graham-linehan-under-fire-for-comparing-trans-activism-to-nazism/19884/ | title=GRAHAM LINEHAN UNDER FIRE FOR COMPARING TRANS ACTIVISM TO NAZISM | work=Attitude | access-date=2019-10-06 | language=en-UK}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2018/12/11/father-ted-graham-linehan-trans-nazis/|title=Father Ted writer Graham Linehan compares trans activism to Nazism|work=PinkNews|access-date=2019-01-20|language=en-UK}}</ref> In a statement to ''[[PinkNews]]'' about his comments, Linehan said \"when a magazine purportedly for gay people, collaborates in homosexual erasure by indulging the straight fantasy that men can be lesbians, something has gone deeply wrong\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://inews.co.uk/news/graham-linehan-father-ted-writer-trans-activism-nazism/|title=Father Ted writer Graham Linehan compares the trans movement to Nazism|work=iNews|access-date=2019-01-20|language=en-UK}}</ref> Linehan described the [[Pride_in_London#Anti-transgender_protest_controversy|anti-transgender protesters at the 2018 London Pride event]] as \"heroes\".<ref>{{cite tweet | user=glinner | number=1032774490156089344 | date=23 August 2018 | archive-url=http://archive.is/cnJyp | archive-date=6 October 2019 | title=Those women who disrupted Pride in London and New Zealand are fucking heroes. This is a land grab and standing up to it took real guts. If you can't be as brave as them, then just find a way to support them or at least hear them out.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2018/08/24/mara-wilson-matilda-graham-linehan-trans-tweets/|title=Mara Wilson star of 'Matilda' hits out at Graham Linehan trans tweets|work=PinkNews|date=2018-08-24|access-date=2018-10-08|language=en-US}}</ref> \n\nIn January 2019, Linehan expressed concern over the news that [[Mermaids UK (Charity)|Mermaids UK]], a charitable advocacy organisation for transgender children and teenagers, was to receive a \u00a3500,000 lottery grant to open clinics around the United Kingdom. He posted to blogging website [[Mumsnet]] encouraging its users to lobby the [[National Lottery Community Fund]] to reverse their decision.<ref name=\"tr\">{{cite news |title=David Davies 'welcomes' Big Lottery Fund's 'review' of grant to transgender charity |url=https://talkradio.co.uk/news/david-davies-welcomes-big-lottery-funds-review-grant-transgender-charity-18121729229 |accessdate=2 June 2019 |work=talkradio.co.uk |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tnlcommunityfund.org.uk/news/press-releases/2019-02-19/outcome-of-review-of-proposed-mermaids-grant|title=Statement: Outcome of our review into Mermaids UK grant {{!}} The National Lottery Community Fund|website=www.tnlcommunityfund.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-02-19}}</ref> The grant was reviewed,<ref name=\"tr\" /> and ultimately awarded to the Mermaids charity.<ref>{{cite news |title=Trans kids charity Mermaids awarded National Lottery grant following review \u00b7 PinkNews |url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2019/02/19/trans-kids-charity-mermaids-national-lottery-grant-review/ |accessdate=2 June 2019 |work=www.pinknews.co.uk}}</ref> Linehan's comments and online campaigning also led to YouTuber and gamer [[Hbomberguy]] conducting a 57-hour fundraising livestream which raised a further \u00a3270,000 for Mermaids UK.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/twitch-stream-pulls-250000-mermaids-charity-featuring-alexandria-ocasio-1298710|title=Twitch stream pulls in $250,000 for Mermaids charity featuring Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez, Owen Jones and more|first=Steven|last=Asarch|date=2019-01-20|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=2019-01-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-leeds-46961883|title=Gamer Hbomberguy hands funding row charity Donkey Kong boost|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=22 January 2019|accessdate=23 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Linehan was the favourite nominee by viewers to be given ''[[The Last Leg]]''{{'}}s \"Dick of the Year\" award, following the comments he made on social media about transgender people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2019/12/11/graham-linehan-channel-4-dick-of-the-year-the-last-leg-transphobe/|title=\u2018King of the transphobes\u2019 Graham Linehan is dominating the nominations for Channel 4\u2019s D*ck of the Year|last=|first=|date=2019-12-11|website=[[PinkNews]]|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://gcn.ie/graham-linehan-dck-of-the-year/|title=Graham Linehan is front runner to win D*ck of the Year Award|last=Kenny|first=Oisin|work=Gay Community News|date=12 December 2019|access-date=17 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/father-ted-creator-linehan-creates-own-social-network-to-defy-twitter-after-transgender-row-cfzw7xls0|title=Father Ted creator Linehan creates own social network to defy Twitter after transgender row|last=Haugh|first=Ben|work=The Times|date=18 December 2019|access-date=17 February 2020}}</ref> When Linehan expressed interest in winning the award, presenter [[Adam Hills]] disqualified him from receiving it, stating that under the rules, anyone who wants to be named Dick of the Year cannot be.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.beyondthejoke.co.uk/content/8115/last-leg-dick|title=News: The Last Leg Reveals Its Dick of the Year Nominees Explaining Why They Are Leaving One Name Out|date=2019-12-14|website=Beyond The Joke|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref>\n\nIn a February 2020 interview with ''[[Newsnight]]'', Linehan reiterated his view that the  [[Tavistock Centre]]'s practice of treating children with drugs such as puberty blockers is comparable to Nazi [[eugenics]] programs and [[Nazi human experimentation|experiments on children]], and stated that transgender activists had made rape and death threats against feminists.<ref>{{cite web |title=BBC Two - Newsnight, Father Ted creator Graham Linehan on trans rights |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p08305wc |website=BBC |access-date=11 February 2020}}</ref> Following this interview, the UK special envoy for post-Holocaust issues accused Linehan of trivialising the Holocaust.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2020/02/14/lord-eric-pickles-graham-linehan-doctors-transgender-kids-nazi-holocaust/|title=Holocaust memorial boss condemns Graham Linehan for Nazi comments|publisher=[[Pink News]]|date=14 February 2020|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Credits==\n===Television director===\n* ''[[Father Ted]]'' (8 episodes,  1997)\n* ''[[Big Train]]'' (6 episodes, 1998)\n* ''[[Black Books]]'' (6 episodes, 2000)\n* ''[[Little Britain]]'' (1 episode, 2003)\n* ''[[The IT Crowd]]'' (25 episodes, 2006\u201313)\n* ''[[Count Arthur Strong (TV series)|Count Arthur Strong]]'' (20 episodes, 2013\u201317)\n* ''[[The Walshes]]'' (3 episodes, 2013)\n* ''[[Shrink (TV series)|Shrink]]'' (3 episodes, 2017)\nLinehan was also an executive producer of the first series of ''[[The IT Crowd]]'', and an associate producer of one episode of ''[[Father Ted]]''.\n\n===Film director===\n* ''[[Hello Friend]]'' (short, also co-writer, 2003)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Nominated for !! Award !! Category !! Result\n|-\n| 1996 || ''[[Father Ted]]'' || [[BAFTAs]] || Best Comedy (Programme or Series) || {{won}}\n|-\n| 1996 || ''Father Ted'' || [[Writers' Guild of Great Britain]] || TV&nbsp;\u2013 Situation Comedy || {{won}}\n|-\n| 1997 ||  ''Father Ted''  || BAFTAs || Best Comedy (Programme or Series) || {{nom}}\n|-\n| 1997 ||  ''[[Harry Enfield's Television Programme|Harry Enfield and Chums]]''  || Writers' Guild of Great Britain || TV&nbsp;\u2013 Light Entertainment || {{won}}\n|-\n| 1999 || ''[[Big Train]]'' || BAFTAs || Best Light Entertainment (Programme or Series) || {{nom}}\n|-\n| 1999 || ''Father Ted'' || BAFTAs || Best Comedy (Programme or Series) || {{won}}\n|-\n| 2001 || ''[[Black Books]]'' || BAFTAs || Situation Comedy Award || {{won}}\n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[The IT Crowd]]'' || BAFTAs || Best Situation Comedy || {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2008 || ''The IT Crowd'' || BAFTAs || Best Situation Comedy || {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2009 || ''The IT Crowd'' || BAFTAs || Best Situation Comedy || {{won}}\n|-\n| 2009 || ''The IT Crowd'' || [[Irish Film and Television Awards|IFTAs]] || Best Script for Television || {{won}}\n|-\n| 2014 || ''The IT Crowd'' || BAFTAs Television Craft || Writer Comedy || {{won}}\n|-\n| 2014 || ''Count Arthur Strong'' || BAFTAs Television Craft || Writer Comedy || {{nom}}\n|}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{IMDb name|0512627}}\n* {{Screenonline name|id=1205698|name=Graham Linehan}}\n* [https://whythatsdelightful.wordpress.com Why, That's Delightful: Graham Linehan's blog]\n* [https://neonmagazinescans.wordpress.com/category/graham-linehan/ Category Archives: Graham Linehan - Complete scans of Graham's articles written for Neon Magazine]\n* [http://robinkellyuk.blogspot.com/2010/06/graham-linehan-interviews.html Writing for Performance: Graham Linehan interviews and writing advice]\n* {{British Comedy Guide|people|graham_linehan}}\n\n{{Graham Linehan}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Linehan, Graham}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Father Ted]]\n[[Category:Hot Press people]]\n[[Category:Irish abortion-rights activists]]\n[[Category:Irish atheists]]\n[[Category:Irish bloggers]]\n[[Category:Irish comedy writers]]\n[[Category:Irish humorists]]\n[[Category:Irish satirists]]\n[[Category:Irish screenwriters]]\n[[Category:Irish male writers]]\n[[Category:Irish television directors]]\n[[Category:Irish television writers]]\n[[Category:Male screenwriters]]\n[[Category:People from Dublin (city)]]\n[[Category:Testicular cancer survivors]]\n[[Category:Irish expatriates in England]]\n[[Category:Male television writers]]\n[[Category:Male bloggers]]\n[[Category:1968 births]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|Irish screenwriter}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use Irish English|date=February 2014}}\n{{Infobox comedian\n| image = Graham Linehan - 2013 (8735745502) (cropped).jpg\n| caption = Linehan in 2013\n| name = Graham Linehan\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1968|5|22|df=yes}}<ref>{{Cite tweet |user=Glinner |number=205073702465970176 |date=22 May 2012 |title=Anyway, bed. Thanks for the conversation. And the birthday wishes! Yay! 44! Not long now! |access-date=15 February 2019}}</ref>\n| birth_place = [[Dublin]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]]\n| medium = [[Television]], [[film]], [[twitter]]\n| nationality = Irish\n| spouse = Helen Serafinowicz\n| children = 2\n| active = 1991\u2013present \n| genre = [[Observational comedy]], [[surreal humour]]\n| notable_work = ''[[Father Ted]]'', ''[[The IT Crowd]]''\n}}\n\n'''Graham Linehan''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|l|\u026a|n|\u0259|h|\u00e6|n}}, born 22 May 1968) is an Irish comedian who, in collaboration with [[Arthur Mathews (writer)|Arthur Mathews]], has written or co-written a string of television comedies. He created or co-created the sitcoms ''[[Father Ted]]'', ''[[Black Books]]'' and ''[[The IT Crowd]]''.\n\nHe has also written for ''[[Count Arthur Strong (TV series)|Count Arthur Strong]]'', ''[[Brass Eye]]'' and ''[[The Fast Show]]''.\n\n==Personal life==\n\nLinehan attended Plunkett's School in [[Whitehall, Dublin|Whitehall]], followed by [[Catholic University School]], a [[Catholic Church|Roman Catholic]] secondary school for boys located on the southside of central [[Dublin]], before joining ''[[Hot Press]]''.<ref name =\"Church\">{{cite web |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/graham-linehan-ive-come-to-hate-the-church-8665386.html |title=Graham Linehan: 'I've come to hate the church' |first=Gerard |last=Gilbert |work= [[The Independent]] |date=22 June 2013 |accessdate=21 October 2014}}</ref> He also had a column with the magazine In Dublin before moving to [[London]].\n\nLinehan is married to writer Helen Serafinowicz who is the sister of [[Peter Serafinowicz]]; the couple have two children.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Jones|first1=Alice|title=Inside the comic world of Peter Serafinowicz: The spoof video master is heading to Hollywood|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/profiles/inside-the-comic-world-of-peter-serafinowicz-the-spoof-video-master-is-heading-to-hollywood-10279558.html|accessdate=12 July 2015|work=The Independent|date=30 May 2015}}</ref><ref name=guardian>{{cite news|last1=Edemariam|first1=Aida|title=The Saturday Interview: Graham Linehan|url=https://www.theguardian.com/theguardian/2011/jun/11/the-saturday-interview-graham-linehan|accessdate=12 July 2015|work=[[The Guardian]]|date=11 June 2011}}</ref><ref name=Telegraph15>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/culture/tvandradio/11342851/Graham-Linehan-interview-On-the-streets-Twitter-trolls-would-be-considered-sociopaths.html|title=Graham Linehan interview: 'On the streets, Twitter trolls would be considered sociopaths'|first=Guy|last=Kelly|work=The Telegraph|date=16 January 2015}}</ref> In October 2015, Graham and Helen Linehan worked with [[Amnesty International]] on a campaign film calling on the Irish government to repeal [[Eighth Amendment of the Constitution of Ireland|the Eighth Amendment of the Constitution]], which \"acknowledges the right to life of the unborn and, with due regard to the equal right to life of the mother, guarantees in its laws to respect, and, as far as practicable, by its laws to defend and vindicate that right\". The couple revealed their decision for Helen to [[Abortion|abort]] a foetus with [[acrania]] while living in [[England]] in 2004, and their discovery that undergoing the procedure in [[Ireland]] would have been an offence carrying a maximum 14-year prison sentence.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2015/oct/19/graham-helen-linehan-ireland-abortion-amnesty-international |title=How heartbreak led Helen and Graham Linehan to campaign for abortion in Ireland |last=Gentleman |first=Amelia |date=19 October 2015 |work=The Guardian}}</ref>\n\nLinehan is an [[Atheism|atheist]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://whythatsdelightful.wordpress.com/2008/09/18/a-bad-day-for-atheism/|title=A bad day for atheism|date=18 September 2008}}</ref> and in January 2009 helped to publicise the [[Atheist Bus Campaign]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2009/jan/06/atheist-bus-campaign-nationwide|title=Launch of the Atheist Bus Campaign|work=The Guardian|date=6 January 2009}}</ref> He is also an honorary associate of the [[National Secular Society]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.secularism.org.uk/honoraryassociates.html|title=Honorary Associates|website=www.secularism.org.uk|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-08-01}}</ref>\n\nLinehan announced in June 2018 that he was a survivor of [[testicular cancer]].<ref name=\"linehan251\">{{cite podcast |title=Graham Linehan on his cancer journey and Father Ted - The Musical: Episode 251 |url=https://soundcloud.com/an-irishman-abroad/graham-linehan-on-his-cancer-journey-and-father-ted-the-musical-episode-251 |author=Jarlath Regan |edition=251 |date=3 July 2018 |work=[[An Irishman Abroad]] |via=[[SoundCloud]] |accessdate=4 July 2018}}</ref>\n\nLinehan is an active [[Twitter]] user.<ref name=Telegraph15 /> In 2011 he perpetrated a Twitter hoax around [[Osama Bin Laden]] being a fan of ''[[The IT Crowd]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/magazine-13467407|title=Bin Laden and The IT Crowd: Anatomy of a Twitter hoax|date=23 May 2011|work=The Guardian}}</ref> On Friday 13 February 2009, Linehan hosted the first BadMovieClub<ref>{{cite web|url=http://badmovieclub.co.uk |title=BadMovieClub website |publisher=Badmovieclub.co.uk |date= |accessdate=20 August 2009}}</ref> on Twitter.  At 9pm exactly, over 2,000 Twitter users simultaneously pressed 'Play' on the film ''[[The Happening (2008 film)|The Happening]]'' (dir. [[M. Night Shyamalan]] 2008) and continued to tweet whilst watching, creating a collective viewing experience which generated 40,000 tweets in under 2 hours. The BadMovieClub was repeated at 12 midnight on Saturday 14 February, hosted by [[Phill Jupitus]]. In August 2009, when the [[National Health Service]] was being attacked by the [[Republican Party (United States)|Republican Party]] of the [[United States]] during an attempt by [[President of the United States|President]] [[Barack Obama]] to reform the American healthcare system, Linehan created the #welovetheNHS campaign on Twitter in an attempt to fight back in defence of the NHS.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.channel4.com/news/articles/politics/international_politics/linehan+attacks+american+aposliesapos+over+nhs/3308762.html|title=Linehan attacks American 'lies' over NHS|publisher=[[Channel 4]] |date=14 August 2009|accessdate=17 October 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web| last=Jacobson|first=Seth|url=http://www.theweek.co.uk/technology/20567/how-father-ted-creator-graham-linehan-sparked-nhs-backlash-twitter|title=How Father Ted creator Graham Linehan sparked NHS backlash on Twitter|work=[[The First Post]]|date=12 August 2009|accessdate=17 October 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\nLinehan and Mathews first met while working at ''[[Hot Press]]''.<ref>{{cite book |last=Thompson |first=Ben |title=Sunshine on Putty: The Golden Age of British Comedy from Vic Reeves to The Office |year=2010 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=VH_MuFWd0vMC&dq=isbn:9780007375530 |page=289 |publisher=Harper Collins |isbn=9780007375530 |type=eBook |accessdate=22 June 2012}}</ref> In their early collaborations, they were responsible for segments in many sketch shows, including ''[[Alas Smith and Jones]]'', ''[[Harry Enfield and Chums]]'', ''[[The All New Alexei Sayle Show]]'', ''[[The Day Today]]'' and the [[Ted and Ralph]] characters in ''[[The Fast Show]]'' (the characters were created by Linehan and Mathews and played by [[Paul Whitehouse]] and [[Charlie Higson]]). The two men continued their collaboration with ''[[Paris (1994 TV series)|Paris]]''<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/guide/tv/paris/|title=Paris|publisher=[[British Comedy Guide]]}}</ref> (one series, 1994) and ''[[Father Ted]]'' (three series, 1995\u20131998).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/newsfeatures/1996/0425/96042500102.html|title=Daftness should be mandatory in Irish politics|author=Mary Cummins|date=4 April 1996|work=[[Irish Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/weekend/1998/0502/98050200230.html|title=Life after Ted|author=Deirdre Falvey|date=5 May 1998|work=[[Irish Times]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rte.ie/news/2007/0121/ted.html|title=Aran Islands in Father Ted row|date=21 January 2007|publisher=[[RT\u00c9]]}}</ref>  They then wrote the first series of the [[sketch comedy|sketch show]] ''[[Big Train]]'', but Linehan was not involved in the second series.<ref name=digitalfix>{{Cite web | title = Big Train at 20 - interview with Arthur Matthews | work = The Digital Fix | date = 23 July 2018 | accessdate = 13 August 2018 | url = https://www.thedigitalfix.com/television/content/11789/big-train-at-20-an-interview-with-the-shows-co-creator-arthur-matthews/}}</ref>\n\nThey also wrote the \"Dearth of A Salesman\" episode for the series ''[[Coogan's Run]]'', which featured the character Gareth Cheeseman. In late 2003, they were named one of the 50 funniest acts to work in television by ''[[The Observer]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/stage/2003/dec/07/comedy.thebestofbritishcomedy|title=The A-Z of laughter (part two)|date=7 December 2003|work=[[The Observer]]}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Graham Linehan and Jon Ronson at TAM London 2010.jpg|thumb|Graham Linehan with [[Jon Ronson]] at TAM London 2010]]\nLinehan has since written for other shows, including ''[[Brass Eye]]''. With [[Dylan Moran]], he co-wrote the first series of ''[[Black Books]]'', a series to which Mathews also contributed. Linehan has also contributed material to ''[[Blue Jam]]'', and its television adaptation ''[[Jam (TV series)|Jam]]''.\n\nLinehan wrote and directed the 2006 [[Channel 4]] [[situation comedy|sitcom]] ''[[The IT Crowd]]'', in which he sought to move away from the recent British trend towards [[mockumentary|mock-documentary]] comedies. Unlike many series of the time, it was recorded before a studio audience.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.comedy.co.uk/guide/tv/the_it_crowd/interview/|title=The IT Crowd Interviews|year=2006|publisher=[[British Comedy Guide]]}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/weekend/2006/0121/1137626794008.html|title=Brian Boyd: Have You Tried Turning It Off and On Again?|date=21 January 2006|work=[[Irish Times]]}}</ref> In November 2008, he was awarded an [[Emmy Award#International Emmys|International Emmy]] for ''[[The IT Crowd]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.irishtimes.com/newspaper/ireland/2008/1126/1227486583337.html|title=Linehan wins an Emmy for sitcom on the IT set|author=Shane Hegarty|date=26 November 2008|work=[[Irish Times]]}}</ref> In 2013, he wrote and directed ''[[The Walshes]]''. He co-wrote the first series of the BBC sitcom ''[[Motherland (TV series)|Motherland]]'' and directed its pilot episode.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Dowell |first1=Ben |title=BBC orders a full series of middle-class mum sitcom Motherland |url=https://www.radiotimes.com/news/2016-10-06/bbc-orders-a-full-series-of-middle-class-mum-sitcom-motherland/ |website=Radio Times |accessdate=15 October 2019 |language=en}}</ref> In 2018 he and Matthews announced plans for a ''Father Ted'' musical.<ref name=digitalfix/>\n\n===Books===\n\nLinehan and Mathews have had one book published, ''Father Ted: The Complete Scripts'' (Paperback \u2013 Boxtree \u2013 20 October 2000) {{ISBN|0-7522-7235-7}}. They have contributed to various magazines and written surreal liner notes for the popular ''[[Volume magazine|Volume]]'' series of [[alternative music]] compilations.\n\n===Television appearances===\n\nBoth Linehan and Mathews have made cameo appearances in programmes they have written. They also made an appearance in the [[sitcom]] ''[[I'm Alan Partridge]]'' as two Irish TV producers considering [[Alan Partridge]] ([[Steve Coogan]]) for a contract.\n\nLinehan has also appeared in ''[[The Day Today]]'' and in two episodes of ''[[Garth Marenghi's Darkplace]]'', and has had cameos in ''[[Black Books]]'' (series one, episode two, as \"I love books\" Guy, and series one, episode five as Fast Food Customer), and the ''[[Father Ted]]'' episodes \"Good Luck Father Ted\", \"Entertaining Father Stone\", \"Flight Into Terror\", \"Cigarettes, Alcohol and Rollerblading\" and \"Chirpy Burpy Cheap Sheep\". He had cameos in four episodes of ''The IT Crowd'': as Messy Joe's Restaurant Musician, in series one, episode three; the blind sorcerer, in series two, Episode six; as an audience member of Jen's speech, in series three, episode four; and as Beth Gaga Shaggy, in series four, episode three. He appeared in the [[List of rounds in Never Mind the Buzzcocks#Identity Parade|Identity Parade]] round of ''[[Never Mind the Buzzcocks]]''. He has also appeared in the pilot of ''[[Little Britain]]'', as well as in series one, episode four, as a bystander who gets in the way of character [[Kenny Craig]] when he is attempting to hypnotise, from a distance, a man whose car he has crashed into. He also appeared in series one, episode five, in which he played a journalist called Roy Sloan (from ''[[Whizzer and Chips]]'') during a conference with Prime Minister Michael Stevens ([[Anthony Head]]). Linehan was one of the writers interviewed by [[Charlie Brooker]] in a special interview episode of the fifth series of ''Brooker's [[Screenwipe]]'' programme, and again on ''Brooker's [[Gameswipe]]'' in 2010. Linehan also appeared as a guest panellist on ''[[Have I Got News for You]]'' in 2011 and again in 2012, and he made his debut as a guest on the BBC show ''[[QI]]'' in the 11th series (K series) in 2013, receiving a score of \u221219.\n\nIn 2007, a documentary about Linehan, his life and his career was produced by Wildfire Films for [[RT\u00c9 One]]. This documentary explored the art, craft and deeply competitive business of creating contemporary television comedy. The programme features interviews with several of the UK's most successful television comedy writers and performers including [[Steve Coogan]], [[Matt Lucas (comedian)|Matt Lucas]], [[David Walliams]], [[Paul Whitehouse]], [[Griff Rhys Jones]] and [[Ardal O'Hanlon]], all of whom have worked with Linehan. It was directed by Adrian McCarthy and produced by Martha O'Neill and Adam Rynne. In 2011, Linehan also appeared with several members of the cast in [[Channel 4]]'s ''Father Ted Night'', an evening of the writer's favourite episodes and two retrospective documentaries.\n\n===Radio appearances===\n\nOn 6 June 2011, Linehan appeared on BBC Radio 4's ''[[Today (BBC Radio 4)|Today]]'' programme to discuss [[The Ladykillers (play)|his adaptation]] of the Ealing comedy film ''[[The Ladykillers]]'' for the West End stage. During this appearance, Linehan took issue with ''[[Today (BBC Radio 4)|Today]]'' presenter [[Justin Webb]] over what he saw as the attempted staging of an artificial argument between himself and the critic [[Michael Billington (critic)|Michael Billington]]. He later expanded on this criticism in an article published in ''[[The Guardian]]'', saying \"I'm talking about that very specific, very artificial, very ''Today'' programme format of a presenter acting as referee between two people who have been chosen to represent the opposing sides of a manufactured argument. It is a binary view of politics, of life and, as a result, it is also a dishonest one. Replace it with anything \u2013 anything \u2013 because anything would be better\".<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2011/jun/08/today-programme-the-ladykillers-graham-linehan | work=The Guardian | first=Graham | last=Linehan | title=Graham Linehan: My Today programme ambush | date=8 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Other work===\nLinehan's children voiced characters in the 2012 ''[[Adventure Time]]'' episode \"[[Goliad (Adventure Time)|Goliad]]\", with Linehan directing the children while taking the producers' instructions over the phone. Linehan planned to write a sequel episode, and sent versions of the story to the production team.<ref>Ward, Pendleton (Series creator). 2014. \"Goliad\" [Commentary track], ''Adventure Time'' Season Four [DVD], Los Angeles, CA: [[Cartoon Network]].</ref> This episode was never made as ''Adventure Time'' ended in 2018.\n\n== Anti-Transgender activism ==\n\nLinehan has tweeted extensively about [[transgender]] issues, which he became involved in after the airing of a 2008 episode of ''[[The IT Crowd]]'', written by Linehan, drew criticism on Twitter for its storyline in which a character unknowingly dates a trans woman.<ref name=\"irishtimes\"/> Linehan felt the joke had been \"harmless\" and says he did not understand the \"ferocity\" of the response.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Haugh |first1=Ben |title=Father Ted creator Linehan creates own social network to defy Twitter after transgender row |url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/father-ted-creator-linehan-creates-own-social-network-to-defy-twitter-after-transgender-row-cfzw7xls0 |accessdate=11 February 2020 |work=The Times |date=18 December 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nLinehan has described himself as being sceptical of the [[self-identification]] of gender, objecting to \"privileged white people saying you must accept anyone who says they are a woman\". He has said that \"anyone suffering from [[gender dysphoria]] needs to be helped and supported\", and has voiced concern over early transgender intervention for children.<ref name=\"irishtimes\">{{cite news |last1=Falvey |first1=Deirdre |title=Graham Linehan: Trans activists 'don't realise the damage' they do |url=https://www.irishtimes.com/culture/tv-radio-web/graham-linehan-trans-activists-don-t-realise-the-damage-they-do-1.3765979 |accessdate=30 May 2019 |work=The Irish Times |date=21 January 2019 |language=en}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2018, Stephanie Hayden, a transgender woman, sued Linehan for harassment. Hayden alleged that Linehan had shared photos on Twitter of Hayden's family and her life before transition, suggested she was a criminal by revealing a past conviction, and repeatedly [[misgender]]ed her and [[deadname]]d her by using her previous name.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Lyons |first1=Izzy |title=Transgender lawyer launches UK's first 'deadnaming' case against Father Ted writer Graham Linehan |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2018/10/07/transgender-lawyer-launches-uks-first-deadnaming-case-against/ |accessdate=2 June 2019 |work=The Telegraph |date=7 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/father-ted-writer-graham-linehan-warned-by-police-after-trolling-transgender-activist-wqfwqgsxn|title=Father Ted writer Graham Linehan warned by police after 'trolling' transgender activist|last=Coyle|first=Colin|date=2018-10-07|work=The Sunday Times|access-date=2018-10-07|language=en|issn=0956-1382}}</ref> Linehan in turn alleged that Hayden publicised several private addresses linked to his family to silence him.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/culture/2018/oct/07/graham-linehan-police-warning-complaint-by-stephanie-hayden-transgender-activist-twitter|title=Graham Linehan given police warning after complaint by transgender activist|last=Halliday|first=Josh|date=2018-10-07|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-02-20|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> Linehan was issued with a verbal warning by police not to contact Hayden.<ref>{{cite news |title=Father Ted writer given harassment warning |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-45777689 |accessdate=2 June 2019 |date=7 October 2018}}</ref>  \n\nLinehan has compared the medical transition of children to experiments carried out on children in [[Nazi Germany]], saying \"if you were around the time of something terrible happening like Nazism, would you be one of the people who said, 'This is wrong,' despite being opposed?\" In the same interview, he described the trans movement as \"provid[ing] cover\" for \"fetishists, con-men, and simply abusive misogynists\".<ref>{{cite av media | people=Derrick Jensen and Graham Linehan | date=9 December 2018 | title=Resistance Radio - Guest: Graham Linehan | type=Podcast | language=English | url=https://resistanceradioprn.podbean.com/e/resistance-radio-guest-graham-linehan/ | publisher=Podbean | quote=The opposition is so extreme and so frightening that eventually everyone is asking you to stop. \u2018My feeling is that I can\u2019t, because it\u2019s too important. It\u2019s too important to the women in my life and it\u2019s too important to me. \u2018I\u2019m now in a position where I can now answer the question honestly of, if you were around the time of something terrible happening like Nazism, or whatever it happened to be, would you be one of the people who said, \u201cNo, this is wrong\u201d, despite being opposed? I feel happy in myself that I\u2019ve been one of the people standing up and saying \u201cno, this is wrong\u201d, despite everybody telling me not to do it.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url=https://inews.co.uk/news/graham-linehan-father-ted-writer-trans-activism-nazism-187701 | title=Father Ted writer Graham Linehan compares the trans movement to Nazism | work=iNews | access-date=2019-10-06 | language=en-UK}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.attitude.co.uk/article/graham-linehan-under-fire-for-comparing-trans-activism-to-nazism/19884/ | title=GRAHAM LINEHAN UNDER FIRE FOR COMPARING TRANS ACTIVISM TO NAZISM | work=Attitude | access-date=2019-10-06 | language=en-UK}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news| url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2018/12/11/father-ted-graham-linehan-trans-nazis/|title=Father Ted writer Graham Linehan compares trans activism to Nazism|work=PinkNews|access-date=2019-01-20|language=en-UK}}</ref> In a statement to ''[[PinkNews]]'' about his comments, Linehan said \"when a magazine purportedly for gay people, collaborates in homosexual erasure by indulging the straight fantasy that men can be lesbians, something has gone deeply wrong\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://inews.co.uk/news/graham-linehan-father-ted-writer-trans-activism-nazism/|title=Father Ted writer Graham Linehan compares the trans movement to Nazism|work=iNews|access-date=2019-01-20|language=en-UK}}</ref> Linehan described the [[Pride_in_London#Anti-transgender_protest_controversy|anti-transgender protesters at the 2018 London Pride event]] as \"heroes\".<ref>{{cite tweet | user=glinner | number=1032774490156089344 | date=23 August 2018 | archive-url=http://archive.is/cnJyp | archive-date=6 October 2019 | title=Those women who disrupted Pride in London and New Zealand are fucking heroes. This is a land grab and standing up to it took real guts. If you can't be as brave as them, then just find a way to support them or at least hear them out.}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2018/08/24/mara-wilson-matilda-graham-linehan-trans-tweets/|title=Mara Wilson star of 'Matilda' hits out at Graham Linehan trans tweets|work=PinkNews|date=2018-08-24|access-date=2018-10-08|language=en-US}}</ref> \n\nIn January 2019, Linehan expressed concern over the news that [[Mermaids UK (Charity)|Mermaids UK]], a charitable advocacy organisation for transgender children and teenagers, was to receive a \u00a3500,000 lottery grant to open clinics around the United Kingdom. He posted to blogging website [[Mumsnet]] encouraging its users to lobby the [[National Lottery Community Fund]] to reverse their decision.<ref name=\"tr\">{{cite news |title=David Davies 'welcomes' Big Lottery Fund's 'review' of grant to transgender charity |url=https://talkradio.co.uk/news/david-davies-welcomes-big-lottery-funds-review-grant-transgender-charity-18121729229 |accessdate=2 June 2019 |work=talkradio.co.uk |language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.tnlcommunityfund.org.uk/news/press-releases/2019-02-19/outcome-of-review-of-proposed-mermaids-grant|title=Statement: Outcome of our review into Mermaids UK grant {{!}} The National Lottery Community Fund|website=www.tnlcommunityfund.org.uk|language=en|access-date=2019-02-19}}</ref> The grant was reviewed,<ref name=\"tr\" /> and ultimately awarded to the Mermaids charity.<ref>{{cite news |title=Trans kids charity Mermaids awarded National Lottery grant following review \u00b7 PinkNews |url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2019/02/19/trans-kids-charity-mermaids-national-lottery-grant-review/ |accessdate=2 June 2019 |work=www.pinknews.co.uk}}</ref> Linehan's comments and online campaigning also led to YouTuber and gamer [[Hbomberguy]] conducting a 57-hour fundraising livestream which raised a further \u00a3270,000 for Mermaids UK.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsweek.com/twitch-stream-pulls-250000-mermaids-charity-featuring-alexandria-ocasio-1298710|title=Twitch stream pulls in $250,000 for Mermaids charity featuring Alexandria Ocasio-Cortez, Owen Jones and more|first=Steven|last=Asarch|date=2019-01-20|website=Newsweek|language=en|access-date=2019-01-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-england-leeds-46961883|title=Gamer Hbomberguy hands funding row charity Donkey Kong boost|publisher=[[BBC News]]|date=22 January 2019|accessdate=23 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn 2019, Linehan was the favourite nominee by viewers to be given ''[[The Last Leg]]''{{'}}s \"Dick of the Year\" award, following the comments he made on social media about transgender people.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2019/12/11/graham-linehan-channel-4-dick-of-the-year-the-last-leg-transphobe/|title=\u2018King of the transphobes\u2019 Graham Linehan is dominating the nominations for Channel 4\u2019s D*ck of the Year|last=|first=|date=2019-12-11|website=[[PinkNews]]|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-13}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://gcn.ie/graham-linehan-dck-of-the-year/|title=Graham Linehan is front runner to win D*ck of the Year Award|last=Kenny|first=Oisin|work=Gay Community News|date=12 December 2019|access-date=17 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/father-ted-creator-linehan-creates-own-social-network-to-defy-twitter-after-transgender-row-cfzw7xls0|title=Father Ted creator Linehan creates own social network to defy Twitter after transgender row|last=Haugh|first=Ben|work=The Times|date=18 December 2019|access-date=17 February 2020}}</ref> When Linehan expressed interest in winning the award, presenter [[Adam Hills]] disqualified him from receiving it, stating that under the rules, anyone who wants to be named Dick of the Year cannot be.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.beyondthejoke.co.uk/content/8115/last-leg-dick|title=News: The Last Leg Reveals Its Dick of the Year Nominees Explaining Why They Are Leaving One Name Out|date=2019-12-14|website=Beyond The Joke|language=en|access-date=2020-02-29}}</ref>\n\nIn a February 2020 interview with ''[[Newsnight]]'', Linehan reiterated his view that the  [[Tavistock Centre]]'s practice of treating children with drugs such as puberty blockers is comparable to Nazi [[eugenics]] programs and [[Nazi human experimentation|experiments on children]], and stated that transgender activists had made rape and death threats against feminists.<ref>{{cite web |title=BBC Two - Newsnight, Father Ted creator Graham Linehan on trans rights |url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/programmes/p08305wc |website=BBC |access-date=11 February 2020}}</ref> Following this interview, the UK special envoy for post-Holocaust issues accused Linehan of trivialising the Holocaust.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.pinknews.co.uk/2020/02/14/lord-eric-pickles-graham-linehan-doctors-transgender-kids-nazi-holocaust/|title=Holocaust memorial boss condemns Graham Linehan for Nazi comments|publisher=[[Pink News]]|date=14 February 2020|accessdate=15 February 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Credits==\n===Television director===\n* ''[[Father Ted]]'' (8 episodes,  1997)\n* ''[[Big Train]]'' (6 episodes, 1998)\n* ''[[Black Books]]'' (6 episodes, 2000)\n* ''[[Little Britain]]'' (1 episode, 2003)\n* ''[[The IT Crowd]]'' (25 episodes, 2006\u201313)\n* ''[[Count Arthur Strong (TV series)|Count Arthur Strong]]'' (20 episodes, 2013\u201317)\n* ''[[The Walshes]]'' (3 episodes, 2013)\n* ''[[Shrink (TV series)|Shrink]]'' (3 episodes, 2017)\nLinehan was also an executive producer of the first series of ''[[The IT Crowd]]'', and an associate producer of one episode of ''[[Father Ted]]''.\n\n===Film director===\n* ''[[Hello Friend]]'' (short, also co-writer, 2003)\n\n==Awards and nominations==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Nominated for !! Award !! Category !! Result\n|-\n| 1996 || ''[[Father Ted]]'' || [[BAFTAs]] || Best Comedy (Programme or Series) || {{won}}\n|-\n| 1996 || ''Father Ted'' || [[Writers' Guild of Great Britain]] || TV&nbsp;\u2013 Situation Comedy || {{won}}\n|-\n| 1997 ||  ''Father Ted''  || BAFTAs || Best Comedy (Programme or Series) || {{nom}}\n|-\n| 1997 ||  ''[[Harry Enfield's Television Programme|Harry Enfield and Chums]]''  || Writers' Guild of Great Britain || TV&nbsp;\u2013 Light Entertainment || {{won}}\n|-\n| 1999 || ''[[Big Train]]'' || BAFTAs || Best Light Entertainment (Programme or Series) || {{nom}}\n|-\n| 1999 || ''Father Ted'' || BAFTAs || Best Comedy (Programme or Series) || {{won}}\n|-\n| 2001 || ''[[Black Books]]'' || BAFTAs || Situation Comedy Award || {{won}}\n|-\n| 2007 || ''[[The IT Crowd]]'' || BAFTAs || Best Situation Comedy || {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2008 || ''The IT Crowd'' || BAFTAs || Best Situation Comedy || {{nom}}\n|-\n| 2009 || ''The IT Crowd'' || BAFTAs || Best Situation Comedy || {{won}}\n|-\n| 2009 || ''The IT Crowd'' || [[Irish Film and Television Awards|IFTAs]] || Best Script for Television || {{won}}\n|-\n| 2014 || ''The IT Crowd'' || BAFTAs Television Craft || Writer Comedy || {{won}}\n|-\n| 2014 || ''Count Arthur Strong'' || BAFTAs Television Craft || Wri