{"title_page": "F. H. Bradley", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox philosopher\n| name             = F.&nbsp;H. Bradley\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OM|size=100%}}\n| region           = [[Western philosophy]]\n| era              = [[19th-century philosophy]]\n| image            = Francis Herbert Bradley.jpg\n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = Francis Herbert Bradley\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1846|1|30|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = [[Clapham]], England\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|1924|9|18|1846|1|30|df=yes}}\n| death_place      = [[Oxford]], England\n| alma_mater       = [[University College, Oxford]]\n| school_tradition = {{hlist | [[British idealism]] | [[epistemic coherentism]]<ref name=IEP>[https://www.iep.utm.edu/coherent/ Coherentism in Epistemology (Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy)]</ref>}}\n| institutions     = [[Merton College, Oxford]]\n| main_interests   = {{hlist | [[Metaphysics]] | [[ethics]] | [[philosophy of history]] | [[logic]]}}\n| influences       = {{flatlist|\n* [[Johann Gottlieb Fichte]]\n* [[G.&nbsp;W.&nbsp;F. Hegel]]\n* [[Immanuel Kant]]\n* [[F.&nbsp;W.&nbsp;J. Schelling]]\n}}\n| influenced       = {{flatlist|\n* [[Bernard Bosanquet (philosopher)|Bernard Bosanquet]]\n* [[C.&nbsp;A. Campbell]]<ref>[http://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/acref/9780199754694.001.0001/acref-9780199754694-e-350 Campbell, Charles Arthur (The Continuum Encyclopedia of British Philosophy)]</ref>\n* [[T.&nbsp;S. Eliot]]\n* [[James Ward (psychologist)|James Ward]]<ref>[https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/james-ward/ James Ward (Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy)]</ref>\n* [[Alfred North Whitehead]]\n}}\n| notable_ideas    = {{hlist | [[Bradley's regress]] | [[epistemic coherentism]]<ref name=IEP/>}}\n}}\n'''Francis Herbert Bradley''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OM}} (30 January 1846&nbsp;\u2013 18 September 1924) was a [[British idealist]] [[philosopher]]. His most important work was ''[[Appearance and Reality]]'' (1893).<ref name=\"Clark\">{{cite book |author=Clark, Ronald W. |title=The Life of Bertrand Russell |publisher=Jonathan Cape and Weidenfeld & Nicolson |location=London |year=1975 |page=45 |isbn=0 297 77018 7 |oclc= |doi= }}</ref>\n\n==Life==\nBradley was born at [[Clapham]], [[Surrey]], [[England]] (now part of the [[Greater London]] area). He was the child of [[Charles Bradley (preacher)|Charles Bradley]], an [[Evangelicalism|evangelical]] preacher, and Emma Linton, Charles's second wife. [[A. C. Bradley]] was his brother. Educated at [[Cheltenham College]] and [[Marlborough College]], he read, as a teenager, some of [[Immanuel Kant]]'s ''[[Critique of Pure Reason]]''. In 1865, he entered [[University College, Oxford]]. In 1870, he was elected to a fellowship at Oxford's [[Merton College, Oxford|Merton College]] where he remained until his death in 1924. Bradley is buried in Holywell Cemetery in Oxford.\n\nDuring his life, Bradley was a respected philosopher and was granted honorary degrees many times. He was the first British philosopher to be awarded the [[Order of Merit]]. His fellowship at Merton College did not carry any teaching assignments and thus he was free to continue to write. He was famous for his non-[[Epistemological pluralism|pluralistic]] approach to [[philosophy]]. His outlook saw a [[Monism|monistic]] unity, transcending divisions between [[logic]], [[metaphysics]] and [[ethics]].  Consistently, his own view combined monism with absolute idealism. Although Bradley did not think of himself as a [[Hegelian]] philosopher, his own unique brand of philosophy was inspired by, and contained elements of, [[Georg Wilhelm Friedrich Hegel]]'s dialectical method.\n\n==Philosophy==\nBradley rejected the [[utilitarianism|utilitarian]] and [[empiricism|empiricist]] trends in English philosophy represented by [[John Locke]], [[David Hume]], and [[John Stuart Mill]]. Instead, Bradley was a leading member of the [[philosophical movement]] known as [[British idealism]], which was strongly influenced by Kant and the [[German idealism|German idealists]], [[Johann Gottlieb Fichte|Johann Fichte]], [[Friedrich Wilhelm Joseph von Schelling|Friedrich Schelling]], and Hegel, although Bradley tended to downplay his influences.\n\nIn 1909, Bradley published an essay entitled \"On Truth and Coherence\" in the journal ''Mind'' (reprinted in ''[[Essays on Truth and Reality]]''). The essay criticises a form of [[Epistemology#Infallibilism, indefeasibility|infallibilist]] [[foundationalism]] in [[epistemology]]. The philosopher [[Robert Stern (philosopher)|Robert Stern]] has argued that in this paper Bradley defends coherence not as an account of justification but as a criterion or test for truth.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Robert Stern | year = 2004 | title = Coherence as a Test for Truth | journal = Philosophy and Phenomenological Research | volume = 69 | issue = 2 | pages = 296\u2013326\n| jstor = 40040722 }}</ref>\n\n==Moral philosophy==\nBradley's view of morality was driven by his criticism of the idea of [[self]] used in the current utilitarian theories of ethics.<ref>preface, Ethical studies: selected essays, G Herbert Bradley Liberal Arts Press, 1951</ref> He addressed the central question of \"Why should I be moral?\"<ref>Ethical studies: selected essays, G Herbert Bradley Liberal Arts Press, 1951 p6.</ref>\n\nHe opposed [[individualism]], instead defending the view of self and morality as essentially social. Bradley held that our moral duty was founded on the need to cultivate our ideal \"good self\" in opposition to our \"bad self\".<ref>Ethical studies: selected essays, G Herbert Bradley Liberal Arts Press, 1951, p153</ref> However, he acknowledged that society could not be the source of our moral life, of our quest to realise our ideal self. For example, some societies may need moral reform from within, and this reform is based on standards which must come from elsewhere than the standards of that society.<ref>[http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/bradley/#Ethics Francis Herbert Bradley (Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy)]</ref>\n\nHe made the best of this admission in suggesting<ref>Ethical studies: selected essays, G Herbert Bradley Liberal Arts Press, 1951, final essay: Selfishness and self-sacrifice</ref> that the ideal self can be realised through following religion.\n\nHis views of the social self in his moral theorising are relevant to the views of Fichte, [[George Herbert Mead]], and [[pragmatism]]. They are also compatible with modern views such as those of [[Richard Rorty]] and [[anti-individualism]] approaches.<ref>Goldberg, Sanford (2007). Anti-individualism: mind and language, knowledge and justification. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press.</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nBradley's philosophical reputation declined greatly after his death. British idealism was practically eliminated by [[G.E. Moore]] and [[Bertrand Russell]] in the early 1900s. Bradley was also famously criticised in [[A. J. Ayer]]'s logical positivist work ''[[Language, Truth and Logic]]'' for making statements that do not meet the requirements of positivist [[verification principle]]; e.g., statements such as \"The Absolute enters into, but is itself incapable of, evolution and progress.\"\nThere has in recent years, however, been a resurgence of interest in Bradley's and other idealist philosophers' work in the Anglo-American academic community.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Mallinson|first1=Jane|title=T.S. Eliot's interpretation of F.H. Bradley : seven essays|date=2002|publisher=Kluwer Academic Publishers|location=Dordrecht ; Boston|isbn=1402009887|pages=1\u20132}}</ref>\n\nIn 1914, a then-unknown [[T. S. Eliot]] wrote his dissertation for a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] from the Department of Philosophy at [[Harvard University]] on Bradley. It was entitled ''Knowledge and Experience in the Philosophy of F. H. Bradley''. Due to tensions leading up to and starting the [[First World War]], Eliot was unable to return to Harvard for his oral defence, resulting in the University never conferring the degree.\n\n==Books and publications==\n* ''Ethical Studies'', (1876), Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1927, 1988.\n* ''The Presuppositions Of Critical History'' (1876), Chicago: Quadrangle Books, 1968.\n* ''The Principles of Logic'' (1883), London: Oxford University Press, 1922. ([https://archive.org/details/theprinciplesofl01braduoft ''Volume 1''])/([https://archive.org/details/theprinciplesofl02braduoft ''Volume 2''])\n* ''Appearance and Reality'' (1893), London: S. Sonnenschein; New York: Macmillan. ([https://archive.org/details/appearanceandrea00braduoft ''1916 edition''])\n* [https://archive.org/details/essaysontruthand00braduoft ''Essays on Truth and Reality''], Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1914.\n* ''Collected Essays'', vols. 1\u20132, Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1935.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Bradley's regress]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikisource author}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{cite SEP |url-id=bradley |title=Francis Herbert Bradley |last=Candlish |first=Stewart}}\n* [http://www.britannica.com/eb/article-9016119/F-H-Bradley Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]\n* [https://archive.org/details/ethicalstudiesse00brad Selected essays from Ethical Studies]\n* [https://archive.org/details/appearanceandrea00braduoft Online text of Appearance and Reality]\n* [http://www.anthonyflood.com/bradleyxnmorality.htm Francis Herbert Bradley, An Unpublished Note on Christian Morality] on AnthonyFlood.com\n* [http://website2.net/bradleypage.html Summaries of F.H. Bradley's ethical arguments]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bradley, Francis Herbert}}\n[[Category:1846 births]]\n[[Category:1924 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Clapham]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:19th-century British philosophers]]\n[[Category:20th-century British philosophers]]\n[[Category:British philosophers]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of language]]\n[[Category:Idealists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Merton College, Oxford]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox philosopher\n| name             = F.&nbsp;H. Bradley\n| honorific_suffix = {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OM|size=100%}}\n| region           = [[Western philosophy]]\n| era              = [[19th-century philosophy]]\n| image            = Francis Herbert Bradley.jpg\n| caption          = \n| birth_name       = Francis Herbert Bradley\n| birth_date       = {{birth date|1846|1|30|df=yes}}\n| birth_place      = [[Clapham]], England\n| death_date       = {{death date and age|1924|9|18|1846|1|30|df=yes}}\n| death_place      = [[Oxford]], England\n| alma_mater       = [[University College, Oxford]]\n| school_tradition = {{hlist | [[British idealism]] | [[epistemic coherentism]]<ref name=IEP>[https://www.iep.utm.edu/coherent/ Coherentism in Epistemology (Internet Encyclopedia of Philosophy)]</ref>}}\n| institutions     = [[Merton College, Oxford]]\n| main_interests   = {{hlist | [[Metaphysics]] | [[ethics]] | [[philosophy of history]] | [[logic]]}}\n| influences       = {{flatlist|\n* [[Johann Gottlieb Fichte]]\n* [[G.&nbsp;W.&nbsp;F. Hegel]]\n* [[Immanuel Kant]]\n* [[F.&nbsp;W.&nbsp;J. Schelling]]\n}}\n| influenced       = {{flatlist|\n* [[Bernard Bosanquet (philosopher)|Bernard Bosanquet]]\n* [[C.&nbsp;A. Campbell]]<ref>[http://www.oxfordreference.com/view/10.1093/acref/9780199754694.001.0001/acref-9780199754694-e-350 Campbell, Charles Arthur (The Continuum Encyclopedia of British Philosophy)]</ref>\n* [[T.&nbsp;S. Eliot]]\n* [[James Ward (psychologist)|James Ward]]<ref>[https://plato.stanford.edu/entries/james-ward/ James Ward (Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy)]</ref>\n* [[Alfred North Whitehead]]\n}}\n| notable_ideas    = {{hlist | [[Bradley's regress]] | [[epistemic coherentism]]<ref name=IEP/>}}\n}}\n'''Francis Herbert Bradley''' {{post-nominals|country=GBR|OM}} (30 January 1846&nbsp;\u2013 18 September 1924) was a [[British idealist]] [[philosopher]]. His most important work was ''[[Appearance and Reality]]'' (1893).<ref name=\"Clark\">{{cite book |author=Clark, Ronald W. |title=The Life of Bertrand Russell |publisher=Jonathan Cape and Weidenfeld & Nicolson |location=London |year=1975 |page=45 |isbn=0 297 77018 7 |oclc= |doi= }}</ref>\n\n==Life==\nBradley was born at [[Clapham]], [[Surrey]], [[England]] (now part of the [[Greater London]] area). He was the child of [[Charles Bradley (preacher)|Charles Bradley]], an [[Evangelicalism|evangelical]] preacher, and Emma Linton, Charles's second wife. [[A. C. Bradley]] was his brother. Educated at [[Cheltenham College]] and [[Marlborough College]], he read, as a teenager, some of [[Immanuel Kant]]'s ''[[Critique of Pure Reason]]''. In 1865, he entered [[University College, Oxford]]. In 1870, he was elected to a fellowship at Oxford's [[Merton College, Oxford|Merton College]] where he remained until his death in 1924. Bradley is buried in Holywell Cemetery in Oxford.\n\nDuring his life, Bradley was a respected philosopher and was granted honorary degrees many times. He was the first British philosopher to be awarded the [[Order of Merit]]. His fellowship at Merton College did not carry any teaching assignments and thus he was free to continue to write. He was famous for his non-[[Epistemological pluralism|pluralistic]] approach to [[philosophy]]. His outlook saw a [[Monism|monistic]] unity, transcending divisions between [[logic]], [[metaphysics]] and [[ethics]].  Consistently, his own view combined monism with absolute idealism. Although Bradley did not think of himself as a [[Hegelian]] philosopher, his own unique brand of philosophy was inspired by, and contained elements of, [[Georg Wilhelm Friedrich Hegel]]'s dialectical method.\n\n==Philosophy==\nBradley rejected the [[utilitarianism|utilitarian]] and [[empiricism|empiricist]] trends in English philosophy represented by [[John Locke]], [[David Hume]], and [[John Stuart Mill]]. Instead, Bradley was a leading member of the [[philosophical movement]] known as [[British idealism]], which was strongly influenced by Kant and the [[German idealism|German idealists]], [[Johann Gottlieb Fichte|Johann Fichte]], [[Friedrich Wilhelm Joseph von Schelling|Friedrich Schelling]], and Hegel, although Bradley tended to downplay his influences.\n\nIn 1909, Bradley published an essay entitled \"On Truth and Coherence\" in the journal ''Mind'' (reprinted in ''[[Essays on Truth and Reality]]''). The essay criticises a form of [[Epistemology#Infallibilism, indefeasibility|infallibilist]] [[foundationalism]] in [[epistemology]]. The philosopher [[Robert Stern (philosopher)|Robert Stern]] has argued that in this paper Bradley defends coherence not as an account of justification but as a criterion or test for truth.<ref>{{cite journal | author = Robert Stern | year = 2004 | title = Coherence as a Test for Truth | journal = Philosophy and Phenomenological Research | volume = 69 | issue = 2 | pages = 296\u2013326\n| jstor = 40040722 }}</ref>\n\n==Moral philosophy==\nBradley's view of morality was driven by his criticism of the idea of [[self]] used in the current utilitarian theories of ethics.<ref>preface, Ethical studies: selected essays, G Herbert Bradley Liberal Arts Press, 1951</ref> He addressed the central question of \"Why should I be moral?\"<ref>Ethical studies: selected essays, G Herbert Bradley Liberal Arts Press, 1951 p6.</ref>\n\nHe opposed [[individualism]], instead defending the view of self and morality as essentially social. Bradley held that our moral duty was founded on the need to cultivate our ideal \"good self\" in opposition to our \"bad self\".<ref>Ethical studies: selected essays, G Herbert Bradley Liberal Arts Press, 1951, p153</ref> However, he acknowledged that society could not be the source of our moral life, of our quest to realise our ideal self. For example, some societies may need moral reform from within, and this reform is based on standards which must come from elsewhere than the standards of that society.<ref>[http://plato.stanford.edu/entries/bradley/#Ethics Francis Herbert Bradley (Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy)]</ref>\n\nHe made the best of this admission in suggesting<ref>Ethical studies: selected essays, G Herbert Bradley Liberal Arts Press, 1951, final essay: Selfishness and self-sacrifice</ref> that the ideal self can be realised through following religion.\n\nHis views of the social self in his moral theorising are relevant to the views of Fichte, [[George Herbert Mead]], and [[pragmatism]]. They are also compatible with modern views such as those of [[Richard Rorty]] and [[anti-individualism]] approaches.<ref>Goldberg, Sanford (2007). Anti-individualism: mind and language, knowledge and justification. Cambridge: Cambridge University Press.</ref>\n\n==Legacy==\nBradley's philosophical reputation declined greatly after his death. British idealism was practically eliminated by [[G.E. Moore]] and [[Bertrand Russell]] in the early 1900s. Bradley was also famously criticised in [[A. J. Ayer]]'s logical positivist work ''[[Language, Truth and Logic]]'' for making statements that do not meet the requirements of positivist [[verification principle]]; e.g., statements such as \"The Absolute enters into, but is itself incapable of, evolution and progress.\"\nThere has in recent years, however, been a resurgence of interest in Bradley's and other idealist philosophers' work in the Anglo-American academic community.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Mallinson|first1=Jane|title=T.S. Eliot's interpretation of F.H. Bradley : seven essays|date=2002|publisher=Kluwer Academic Publishers|location=Dordrecht ; Boston|isbn=1402009887|pages=1\u20132}}</ref>\n\nIn 1914, a then-unknown [[T. S. Eliot]] wrote his dissertation for a [[Doctor of Philosophy|PhD]] from the Department of Philosophy at [[Harvard University]] on Bradley. It was entitled ''Knowledge and Experience in the Philosophy of F. H. Bradley''. Due to tensions leading up to and starting the [[First World War]], Eliot was unable to return to Harvard for his oral defence, resulting in the University never conferring the degree.\n\n==Books and publications==\n* ''Ethical Studies'', (1876), Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1927, 1988.\n* ''The Presuppositions Of Critical History'' (1876), Chicago: Quadrangle Books, 1968.\n* ''The Principles of Logic'' (1883), London: Oxford University Press, 1922. ([https://archive.org/details/theprinciplesofl01braduoft ''Volume 1''])/([https://archive.org/details/theprinciplesofl02braduoft ''Volume 2''])\n* ''Appearance and Reality'' (1893), London: S. Sonnenschein; New York: Macmillan. ([https://archive.org/details/appearanceandrea00braduoft ''1916 edition''])\n* [https://archive.org/details/essaysontruthand00braduoft ''Essays on Truth and Reality''], Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1914.\n* ''Collected Essays'', vols. 1\u20132, Oxford: Clarendon Press, 1935.\n\n==See also==\n*[[Bradley's regress]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{wikisource author}}\n{{wikiquote}}\n* {{cite SEP |url-id=bradley |title=Francis Herbert Bradley |last=Candlish |first=Stewart}}\n* [http://www.britannica.com/eb/article-9016119/F-H-Bradley Encyclop\u00e6dia Britannica]\n* [https://archive.org/details/ethicalstudiesse00brad Selected essays from Ethical Studies]\n* [https://archive.org/details/appearanceandrea00braduoft Online text of Appearance and Reality]\n* [http://www.anthonyflood.com/bradleyxnmorality.htm Francis Herbert Bradley, An Unpublished Note on Christian Morality] on AnthonyFlood.com\n* [http://website2.net/bradleypage.html Summaries of F.H. Bradley's ethical arguments]\n*[https://www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLVb_FXQVmlzXMuiR02iHU9VORRlppw7Qn Selected Recordings of F.H. Bradley's Writings]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Bradley, Francis Herbert}}\n[[Category:1846 births]]\n[[Category:1924 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Clapham]]\n[[Category:Alumni of University College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:19th-century British philosophers]]\n[[Category:20th-century British philosophers]]\n[[Category:British philosophers]]\n[[Category:Philosophers of language]]\n[[Category:Idealists]]\n[[Category:Fellows of Merton College, Oxford]]\n", "name_user": "XLinkBot", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(BOT--Reverting link addition(s) byFobidiumto revision 941136335 (www.youtube.com/playlist?list=PLVb_FXQVmlzXMuiR02iHU9VORRlppw7Qn [\\byoutube\\.com]))", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/F._H._Bradley"}
